<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Resumes Exercise of Sovereignty over Hong Kong (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Humen Town in the city of Dongguan, Guangdong Province,
people set off fireworks to commemorate martyrs, especially Lin
Zexu, a special envoy sent by the Qing Dynasty emperor to ban the
British opium trade.
</P>
<P>
In China, Lin Zexu is regarded as a national hero for
destroying tens of thousands of cases of opium brought from
Britain at Humen Town in 1839.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt that the historic event of Hong Kong's
return will greatly inspire the patriotic enthusiasm of our
generation," said Ling Qing, a fifth-generation descendant of Lin
Zexu.
</P>
<P>
In modern-day China, patriotism is best embodied through the
promotion of China's reform, opening to the outside world and
modernization drive under the leadership of the Communist Party,
said Ling Qing.
</P>
<P>
The great event has also received favorable reaction from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
Kofi A. Annan, secretary-general of the United Nations, said in
an earlier interview that all people, including those in Hong
Kong, China's interior areas, and in other countries and regions,
will benefit from the event.
</P>
<P>
Polls have shown that the 6.3 million people in Hong Kong are
confident in their future.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, first chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, said that July 1 would be perceived as the
beginning of a new era rather than the end of a historical period
of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will enter the 21st century with considerable merits,
Tung Chee Hwa said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
