<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot, Greek Presidents Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
held talks here today with his Greek counterpart, Costis
Stephanopoulos, on coordinating their actions prior to Clerides'
direct talks with Turkish-Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Clerides, who is visiting Greece, meets Denktash in New York
under United Nations auspices on July 9.
</P>
<P>
Clerides will jointly chair a meeting Tuesday with Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis on the stance to be taken at the
forthcoming talks.
</P>
<P>
However, Clerides said before his arrival that his talks with
Greek leaders aimed at better coordination instead of any change
in positions.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Under-Secretary Yiannos Kranidiotis told a press
conference that Clerides' presence at Tuesday's meeting would be
"an opportunity for Greece and Cyprus to confer on strategies and
tactics."
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis said he hoped that the New York talks would
produce "a positive outcome". He said the Greek diplomatic
delegation to New York would be headed by Alexandros Sandis, Greek
Ambassador to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish Troops
occupied the northern part of the island following a coup plotted
by the then ruling junta in Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
