<HEADLINE> Grand Celebrations in Tianjin To Welcome Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- With torches in hand, 200 runners
embarked on the final leg of a race tonight in northern Tianjin
Municipality to welcome Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Other runners joined the team as it passed two relay points,
and a total of 600 reached the final destination, the municipal
Youth's Palace, where 1,397 more torch-bearers were waiting for
them.
</P>
<P>
All 1,997 runners gathered at the square of the city's railway
station, and arranged themselves so that their torches formed the
Chinese characters "Hui Gui," which means "return."
</P>
<P>
As the digital countdown clock on the square ticked off the
last ten seconds till midnight, the entire crowd counted down in
unison from 10 to 1.
</P>
<P>
At the zero hour on July 1, 1997, with the handover ceremony of
Hong Kong broadcast live from a TV screen on the square, the whole
city was swept up in the fireworks displays, deafening cheers and
festive atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, fireworks also illuminated the night sky over
Dagukou Fort near the mouth of the Haihe River, as a symbol of
blowing away the century-long humiliation suffered at the fort
when the British invaded more than 150 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Thousands more Tianjin residents attended a rally near the
fort, located in an area which has already become the most
economically-developed in Tianjin, to unveil a monument and
embrace the final return of Hong Kong to the motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
