<HEADLINE> Transfer of Government Moves On Smoothly: HSBC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- "Business as usual" has become a
shared dictum among the business community in Hong Kong, said
Global Outlook, a British quarterly publication of HSBC.
</P>
<P>
In an article entitled Transfer of Government Moves On
Smoothly, the third issue of Global Outlook 1997 said, "A
strengthening local economy and rising public confidence has
helped the transfer of government to proceed smoothly."
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the upbeat public sentiment, the quarterly said that
both the stock and property markets staged strong rallies in the
first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
So far, Hong Kong's economy has shown resilience despite a
slower-than-expected recovery in external trade. In the first four
months of 1997, exports grew by a 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Retail business continued to gather momentum, rising by 6.1
percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Inflation in Hong Kong remains subdued, moderating to 5.2
percent in April, mainly due to benign food prices. Its more
vibrant economic activity will begin to feed through into higher
prices in the second half of 1997, HSBC expected.
</P>
<P>
Overall, real GDP is estimated to have risen strongly by 6
percent in the first quarter. For the rest of the year, growth
will mainly be driven by strong consumption and investment demand,
Global Outlook said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Employers Optimistic Over Jobs, Says Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Britain's employment prospects are
the brightest since 1989, shortly before its economy dipped into
recession, according to the latest quarterly labor market trends
survey published today by Manpower, the leading job services
company.
</P>
<P>
Looking at job prospects among more than 2,000 employers in the
three months from July to September this year, Manpower said that
29 percent forecast an increase in job levels, with 9 percent
predicting a fall -- an overall net balance of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
This is the highest figure in a Manpower survey since 1989 and
marks an increase of 5 percentage points from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
The strongest sectors for job opportunities over the next three
months will be electronics, clothing, manufacturing, engineering
and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
However, largely domestic sectors such as retail distribution
and construction are also reporting a rise in demand for
employees. The survey also showed strong growth in banking and
other financial services. Lilian Benneth, chairman of Manpower,
said, "Clearly these figures are good news for those seeking
employment and for the country as a whole."
</P>
<P>
However, she warned about increasing upward pressures on wages
and about general recruitment difficulties and skill shortages,
particularly in information technology.
</P>
<P>
The Manpower survey was based on responses this month from
2,067 companies who are the largest employers in the local labor
markets covered by the company's 170 UK officers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
