<HEADLINE> Israeli Foreign Minister Threatens To Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- In another sign indicating a
deepening cabinet crisis, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
declared this afternoon that he would decide in the coming days
whether to remain in the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Levy made the statement at a hastily arranged press
conference held in the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Levy, who was deeply offended by not having been informed of
the meeting between Israeli National Infrastructure Minister
Ariel Sharon and Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO)
Secretary General Abu Mazen on June 16, canceled a scheduled
meeting with Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu Sunday, at which
the two men had been expected to patch up their differences.
</P>
<P>
Levy called off the meeting, which would have been his third
with Netanyahu in the past four days, on Sunday morning only
half-an-hour before it was to take place at 11:30 a.m.. Levy then
shut himself up in his office, rejecting all attempts by the
prime minister's aides to placate him.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the peace process with the Palestinians, Levy
complained that just like Israel's demand on the other side to
live up to its commitment, the Israeli government must also make
decisions.
</P>
<P>
Levy is reportedly worried about the possibility of Sharon's
takeover of his position in charge of the negotiations with the
Palestinians. Sources close to Levy said he insisted that
Netanyahu should make it clear that he, not Sharon, would be in
charge of the peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
However, Levy said that he does not object to Sharon's
involvement in the peace process. What he objects to is that he
was not told about the meeting although he is in charge of the
peace negotiations with the Palestinians, the Israeli foreign
minister added.
</P>
<P>
In light of the growing cabinet crisis, various Israeli parties
are preparing for the possibility of early elections. But Likud
officials dismissed the suggestion that Levy's eventual departure
would lead to the fall of the one-year-old rightwing government.
</P>
</TEXT>
