<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fireworks, Laughter and Tears Fill Beijing at Final Moments of Hong Kong's Homecoming Journey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Minutes before the digital
countdown clock in China's Tiananmen Square ticked down to zero,
an array of fireworks lit up the night sky of the Chinese capital
over hundreds of thousands of Beijingers in the world's largest
square.
</P>
<P>
The square was heaving with jubilant crowds in an all-night
celebration. Some 100,000-plus Beijingers gathered in the square
after dusk, awaiting the final moments of Hong Kong's return to
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
At one minute to midnight, the clock-watchers gradually
calmed down, and only the sounds of chanting and drumbeats could
be heard over the 440,000-square-meter area as the spectators
counted down from 60 to 0.
</P>
<P>
Their voices were amplified and telecast to all parts of the
world through a live broadcast.
</P>
<P>
Tiananmen, or the "Gate of Heavenly Peace," tonight again
witnessed an historic moment in China.
</P>
<P>
Some 48 years ago, it was there the late Chairman Mao Zedong
proclaimed the founding the New China. The Memorial Hall of
Chairman Mao is now located across the road from the countdown
clock.
</P>
<P>
"The helmsman is surely with all of us at this moment," said
Zhang Quanrui, a worker who participated in the building of the
hall.
</P>
<P>
People in the square also held up portraits of Deng Xiaoping,
who initiated and directed the negotiations with the British
Government on Hong Kong's return.
</P>
<P>
The event lasted for more than seven hours, and is said to be
one of world's largest and longest. But the lengthy schedule of
activities hardly dampened the enthusiasm of the attendants.
</P>
<P>
"Actually, the Chinese people had been waiting for this moment
for one and half centuries," said Zhang Zaixing, a professor with
the prestigious Qinghua University.
</P>
<P>
Middle school student Liang Shanshan said, "Even though we will
have final exams soon, all our classmates are eager to join the
celebrations."
</P>
<P>
The celebrations, featuring traditional lion dancing and
Beijing opera performances, were centered around the countdown
clock, located in front of the Museum of the Chinese Revolution.
</P>
<P>
The 16-meter-high digital countdown clock erected in 1994. Li
Weimin, one of the persons who proposed the putting up of the
clock in the square, said, "After the zero hour last night, the
clock is no more a chronometer. Gone is the 100-year history of
humiliation. What the clock really symbolizes is a new chapter in
Chinese history."
</P>
<P>
The clock will be relocated at the foot of the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
Performers tonight staged a party hailing China's unity and the
leadership of the Communist Party of China (CPC). July 1 is also the
76th anniversary of the founding of the CPC.
</P>
<P>
Danzim, a Tibetan college student and his schoolmates from
other ethnic groups demonstrated their folk dances. "We all think
that today is the common festival for all Chinese nationalities,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The celebrations paused as it was nearing 12:00 when the people
began to count down in chorus until the digital clock indicated
zero. Then, the people turned their eyes to the five large TV
screens that were showing the live broadcast of the handover
ceremony held some 2,000 km away in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A flood of cheers burst out from the square when the national
flag of the People's Republic of China and the flag of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region were raised and as the Chinese
President Jiang Zemin declared that Hong Kong's return is "a
victory of justice and the cause of world peace."
</P>
<P>
"Although we have already been waiting for it so long, it
seemed that this night is longer than I had anticipated," said Li
Baoduo, an army officer.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Resumes Exercise of Sovereignty Over Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- China has resumed the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong, ending 156 years of British colonial
rule here, as a five-star red flag was raised at zero hour today
after the lowering of the Union Jack of Britain.
</P>
<P>
The wish cherished by the Chinese people for one and a half
centuries has come true.
</P>
<P>
"July 1, 1997 will go down in the annals of history as a day
that merits eternal memory," Chinese President Jiang Zemin
proclaimed at the Hong Kong handover ceremony hosted by the
Chinese and British governments in the Grand Hall on level five of
the Extension to the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
"The return of Hong Kong to the motherland after going through
more than a century of vicissitudes indicates that from now on,
Hong Kong compatriots have become true masters of this Chinese
land and that Hong Kong has now entered a new era of development,"
Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
His speech drew rousing applause from more than 4,000 Chinese
and foreign dignitaries in the hall. The scene was televised live
to billions of people across the world.
</P>
<P>
The handover ceremony began at 23:42, June 30.
</P>
<P>
At 23:46, amid music and applause, Chinese President Jiang
Zemin, Premier Li Peng, Vice-Premier Qian Qichen, Vice-Chairman of
the Central Military Commission Zhang Wannian and HKSAR Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa entered the hall and sat in chairs on the
rostrum. Also seated at the rostrum, from the British side, were
Prince Charles, Prime Minister Tony Blair, Foreign Minister Robin
Cook, departing Hong Kong Governor Chris Patten and Chief of
Defense Staff Sir Charles Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
After the guards of honor from both countries had performed
their military salute, Prince Charles delivered a speech. He said
the important and special ceremony marked the restoration of Hong
Kong to the People's Republic of China, under the terms of the
Sino-British Joint Declaration of 1984, after more than 150 years
of British administration.
</P>
<P>
He paid tribute to those who had turned the concept of "one
country, two systems" into the Joint Declaration, and to the
dedication and commitment of those who had worked so hard over the
last 13 years to negotiate the details of the Joint Declaration's
implementation.
</P>
<P>
The heir to the British throne said Hong Kong has shown the
world how dynamism and stability can be defining characteristics
of a successful society.
</P>
<P>
When the flag lowering and raising ceremony that signified the
transfer of power in Hong Kong began, all people in the hall
focused their attention on the flagpoles standing on both sides of
the rostrum.
</P>
<P>
At 23:59, the British national flag and the British Hong Kong
flag were lowered slowly amid the sound of the British national
anthem. The Union Jack of Britain, which had flown over Hong Kong
for more than 150 years, came completly down in about 50 seconds,
signifying the end of British colonial rule of as many years in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
At zero hour today, amid the sound of the national anthem of
the People's Republic of China, the five-star red flag of the
nation, accompanied by the bauhinia regional flag of the Hong Kong
Special Administration Region (HKSAR), rose slowly.
</P>
<P>
The entire hall burst with resounding applause, and tears welled
up in the eyes of many people.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people have struggled for one and a half centuries
for this historic moment. Hong Kong, which includes Hong Kong
Island, Kowloon and the "New Territories," has been Chinese
territory since ancient times. After the Opium War in 1940,
Britain forced the Qing government of China into signing three
unequal treaties, grabbing by force and "leasing" this piece of
Chinese territory. The Chinese people never ceased struggles
against British occupation of Hong Kong in the past years.
</P>
<P>
Today, Hong Kong has returned to China, and the Chinese head of
state stands on this part of Chinese territory for the first time
in history.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the handover ceremony, Jiang Zemin said history
will remember Deng Xiaoping for his creative concept of "one
country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
It is precisely along the course envisaged by this great
concept that China has successfully resolved the Hong Kong
question through diplomatic negotiations and finally achieved Hong
Kong's return to the motherland, he said.
</P>
<P>
With the mention of Deng Xiaoping's name, the entire hall was
filled with gratitude for the founder of the great cause of Hong
Kong's return. Attention was directed toward Madame Zhuo Lin, the
widow of the late Chinese leader.
</P>
<P>
Deng had expressed on many occasions that he would visit Hong
Kong upon its return to China even if he has to go there in a
wheelchair. Regretably, he passed away several months ago. Zhuo
Lin's presence at today's handover ceremony, in a sense, has
fulfilled Deng's long-cherished wish.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Jiang Zemin reiterated that, after the return of
Hong Kong, the Chinese government will unswervingly implement the
Chinese government's Hong Kong-related basic policies of "one
country, two systems," "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong" and
a high degree of autonomy and keep Hong Kong's previous
socio-economic system and way of life unchanged and its previous
laws basically unchanged.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Central People's Government shall be
responsible for Hong Kong-related foreign affairs and Hong Kong's
defense, that the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region shall be
vested, in accordance with the Basic Law, with executive power,
legislative power and independent judicial power, including that
of final adjudication, that Hong Kong people shall enjoy various
rights and freedoms in accordance with law, and that the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region shall gradually develop a democratic
system that suits Hong Kong's reality.
</P>
<P>
He said the legitimate economic interests of all countries and
regions in Hong Kong shall be protected by law. He expressed the
hope that all countries and regions that have investment and trade
interests in Hong Kong would continue to contribute to the
prosperity and stability of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin's speech was often interrupted by applause.
</P>
<P>
The entire handover ceremony ended at 0:12, July 1.
</P>
<P>
Present at the midnight handover ceremony were representatives
from more than 40 countries and regions, consul-generals and
consuls of nearly 100 countries in Hong Kong, leading officials
from 30 international and regional organizations and celebrities
from different parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
Attending the ceremony were also representatives from different
walks of life in Hong Kong, compatriots from Macao and Taiwan, and
representatives of overseas Chinese and foreigners of Chinese
origin in more than 30 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
More than 8,000 reporters from over 700 media organizations in
different parts of the world covered the historic event.
</P>
</TEXT>
