<HEADLINE> Urgent: Inauguration of HKSAR, Arrival of Chinese Leaders (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Central Delegation headed by
Chinese state leaders has entered the main hall at level seven of
the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony for the inauguration of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) and the swearing-in of the HKSAR
government will begin very soon.
</P>
<P>
Walking into the main hall, amid enthusiastic applause, are
Jiang Zemin, general secretary of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), state president and chairman of
the Central Military Commission (CMC), Li Peng, premier of the
State Council, Qian Qichen, vice premier, Wang Hanbin, vice
chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress, Zhang Wannian, CMC vice chairman, and Tung Chee Hwa,
chief executive of the HKSAR. They are seated in the front row on
the rostrum. Other members of the Central Delegation have also
taken their seats on the rostrum.
</P>
<P>
More than 4,000 representatives and guests from all parts of
the world, who have just attended the Hong Kong handover ceremony,
are already seated in the hall with a floor space of 8,500 square
meters.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 journalists holding special permits for
on-the-spot coverage of the ceremony have waited in a designated
area of the hall for hours. The appearance of the Chinese leaders
is accompanied by a burst of camera flash lights and the click of
camera shutters.
</P>
<P>
The hall at level seven, the venue for the inauguration and
swearing-in ceremony, exhumes a solemn atmosphere. At the front of
the hall hang a five-star red Flag and the regional flag of the
HKSAR featuring a bauhinia. At the front of the rostrum are
hundreds of pots of flowers. Two giant TV screens flanking the
rostrum will show ceremony proceedings live. People in all parts
of the world will be able to witness the process of the HKSAR
inauguration via live TV broadcast.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, subjected to 156 years of British colonial rule,
will enter a new era of "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong"
after Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the HKSAR, and other SAR
government officials, who are all Hong Kong residents, have been
sworn in.
</P>
</TEXT>
