<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, DPRK, South Korean Officials Hold New Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Officials from the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), South Korea and the United
States today began their new round of talks for a peace treaty to
end the 1950-53 Korea War, a U.S. State Department official said.
</P>
<P>
The one-day talks are being held in a New York hotel, the U.S.
official told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK delegation is headed by Vice Foreign Minister Kim Gye
Gwan while the head of South Korea's delegation is Deputy Foreign
Minister Song Yong Shik.
</P>
<P>
Senior envoys of the three parties appeared to be in a relaxed
mood, shaking hands and exchanging pleasantries before starting
talks, according to the U.S. official.
</P>
<P>
The current meeting is a follow-up to the one held in March in
New York to discuss the proposed four-way peace talks aimed at
replacing the armistice of 1953 with a formal peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
The four-way talks, which would eventually also include China,
were proposed in April 1996 when U.S. President Bill Clinton
visited Seoul.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK and South Korean delegation leaders told each other
that they hoped for a good result from the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
