<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Revelers Mark Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, the largest industrial
city of China, was lit up by 800,000 red lanterns tonight and the
banks of the Huangpu River that swerves through the city's
downtown were a sea of jubilant and singing crowds as more than
10,000 Shanghai residents gathered to celebrate the return of Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
"One hundred years ago, I was hopelessly watching you leave; a
century later, I am here awaiting your homecoming," were the
lyrics to one tune.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, festooned with 800,000 lanterns and decorated with
two million pots of flowers, was once forced to lease its port to
western nations. Tonight, the city's streets were swarming with
hundreds of thousands of people celebrating the historic handover.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai Bund Park, which was set up by British colonialists
and used to be notorious for a signboard that read "No Trespassing
for Chinese," about 2,500 people sitting in front of the countdown
clock cheered when the city's bell tower struck twelve times.
</P>
<P>
As the people saw the national flag of the People's Republic of
China was raised in Hong Kong through the live broadcast by a
large TV screen, they could not help but burst into the singing of
the national anthem. Their exciting faces were illuminated by the
fireworks blazing through the sky. Industrial workers beat drums
and gongs; youngsters rose into lion and dragon dances. Children
with color flags in their hands jumped with joy. Grey-haired
professors clasped each other, so excited that tears were rolling
down their cheeks.
</P>
<P>
Du Xuan, 84-year-old playwright of a drama on Hong Kong's
return newly staged in Shanghai, said that he worked for years in
Hong Kong before the founding of the People's Republic of China,
and had witnessed the great changes that have taken place in the
island over the past few decades.
</P>
<P>
"The return of Hong Kong is an historical event that signals a
brighter future for Hong Kong," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0051 </DOCNO>
