<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1700 GMT, June 30 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG -- At the zero hour of July 1, 1997, the Hong Kong
handover ceremony was being held at the new annex of the Hong Kong
Convention and Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese five-star national flag was slowly hoisted to the
top of the flagpole where the Union Jack fluttered about a minute
before, marking the end of more than 150 years of British colonial
rule in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin said here today
that China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over Hong
Kong is both a festival for the Chinese nation and a victory for
the universal cause of peace and justice.
</P>
<P>
"In accordance with the Sino-British Joint Declaration on the
question of Hong Kong, the two governments have held on schedule
the handover ceremony to mark China's resumption of the exercise
of sovereignty over Hong Kong and the official establishment of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of the People's
Republic of China," Jiang said at the ceremony for the handover of
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Center-right Motherland Party (ANAP) Chairman Mesut
Yilmaz announced here Monday that he has become the prime
minister of Turkey's 55th government.
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's private enterprises are optimistic about Hong
Kong's role as an international financial center after its return
to China on July 1, business leaders here said today.
</P>
<P>
"I'm pretty sure that Hong Kong will continue to grow as an
international financial and trade center," said Minoru Murofushi,
president of Japan's major trading house Itochu Corp.
</P>
<P>
LUANDA -- United Nations Special Envoy to Angola Blondin Beye
today expressed satisfaction over UN Security Council's resolution
to replace the current Rectification Mission with a UN observation
mission.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council, he said, supports the suggestions by the
Joint Commission for Angolan Peace Process concerning tensions in
north-east Angola, demanding that the Angolan government honor
its own promises and stop offensive activities.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey President Suleyman Demirel has approved the
new government led by Motherland Party (ANAP) leader Mesut Yimaz.
</P>
<P>
Yimaz made the announcement at the presidential palace at noon
after Demirel held a one-hour-long meeting with him for the
approval of the coalition government consisting of the ANAP,
Democratic Left Party (DSP), and Democratic Turkey Party (DTP).
</P>
</TEXT>
