<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flight Dispute Claims Four More Lives in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- At least four employees from a
local travel agency were killed by armed men in an ambush outside
Modasishu yesterday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Ballidogle Airport, the travel
agency staff were ambushed by gunmen equipped with technical
vehicle, on their way to the airport.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the Air Djibouti employees had been accompanied
by two armed wagons with more than 20 heavily militiamen who
returned fire as the ambush started.
</P>
<P>
A contract dispute between the current contractor of Air
Djibouti and a former contractor of the agency whose job was
terminated as the contract is renewed for the new contractor
early in the year, is said to be the cause of the ambush.
</P>
<P>
The current contractor has been one of the employees of the
former contractor.
</P>
<P>
In a similar attack last week, one person was killed and 11
others were wounded when the same group who carried out
yesterday's ambush had attacked the employees of the agency on
the road to Ballidogle.
</P>
<P>
Traffic on Ballidogle road has been suspended for a while, but
returned back to normal after the attack.
</P>
<P>
The two sides, which belong to the Habar Gidir clan loyal to
Hussein Mohamed Aidid, had been mediated by their clan elders for
several times, but the midiations were proved to be fruitless.
</P>
<P>
Two painted technicals and more than 50 armed men from Hussein
Aidid's faction had intervened and separated the combatant
militiamen at Marehan street of south Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
So far, seven people were killed more than 17 others wounded
since the contract dispute began between the warring sides.
</P>
<P>
The future operation of the agency is uncertain as each side
is determined to control the travel agency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
