<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urgent: HKSAR Inauguration, Speech by Chief Executive (10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), says at the ceremony that "one
country, two systems" is an extraordinary concept.
</P>
<P>
He says that the scope and comprehensiveness of this
groundbreaking model (China's resumption of the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong under the 'one country, two systems'
principle) is the first of its kind in the history of the world.
Hong Kong, under the eyes of the world, will proudly pioneer such
a challenge, he said.
</P>
<P>
He continued, "This concept, novel to most of the world, will
undoubtedly bring with it a set of new challenges. We have no
doubt, however, that Hong Kong will overcome these challenges and
build an even better tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time in history, we, the people of Hong Kong,
will shape our own destiny. We will finally be master of our own
house."
</P>
<P>
He says that the SAR Government is fully committed to
preserving the Hong Kong way of life, maintaining Hong Kong's free
and open economic system, upholding the rule of law, and building
a more democratic and participative society.
</P>
<P>
"We will be compassionate to those in need, and we will
maintain Hong Kong as a vibrant, international and cosmopolitan
hub," he says.
</P>
<P>
He says he will perform, in great dedication, the sacred
responsibility of a high degree of autonomy entrusted by law and
lead the pioneering Hong Kong people on their march on the road of
"one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
Tung, 60, has been made first chief executive of the HKSAR
through an election held in December 1996 and by appointment by
the Central People's Government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
