<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Macao Celebrates HK's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Flags of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) and China waving back and forth,
champagne popping open as the final moment came. Thousands of
Macao residents broke into deafening cheers in a square in central
Macao.
</P>
<P>
They have been singing and dancing all night, waiting for the
countdown to the handover of Hong Kong at midnight on June 30.
Many said it is dream come true not only for Hong Kong citizens,
but also for all Chinese people around the world.
</P>
<P>
"This is the most glorious moment in the history of China,"
said the 90-year-old Choi Moi, a retired worker who was chairman
of a minor trade union in Macao. "I am very happy because it shows
China no longer suffers from bullying by foreign powers."
</P>
<P>
The climax of celebration arrived after days of preliminary
events in Macao, which also returns to the embrace of the
motherland in two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for tonight's celebration began a month ago.
Almost all grassroots organizations, Chinese-funded companies,
associations of different industries in Macao have held activities
to mark the return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Nearly all major buildings in Macao are awash with red lanterns
and banners hailing Hong Kong's return to China. Streets are lit
up. Macao is immersed in a joyful spree of celebration.
</P>
<P>
From 8:30 pm tonight, thousands of people began gathering in
the central square. Organized by the Macao Association of
Neighborhood Committees, the evening party attracted both elderly
citizens and children despite a hot and humid weather.
</P>
<P>
Attendants at the party said they were excited and happy that
Hong Kong has returned to the motherland after more than 150 years
of separation.
</P>
<P>
The 90-year-old Choi Moi sang a piece of Guangdong Opera
tonight, hailing Hong Kong's return and praising the great idea of
"one country, two systems" put forward by Deng Xiaoping. He wrote
the lyrics himself.
</P>
<P>
"I admire Deng's talented design of 'one country, two
systems,'" he sang. "It helps people live happily without changing
their lifestyle."
</P>
<P>
Leung Heng Teng, an organizer of tonight's gala, said that
under the policy of "one country, two systems", he is convinced
that Hong Kong will have a bright future.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will remain prosperous and stable under that policy,
he said. "Just as the policy has helped contribute to a smooth
transition in Hong Kong, it will also be an inspiration to the
transition in Macao."
</P>
<P>
Leung's opinion was shared by the 41-year-old Lao Ion Fai, who
works as a computer engineer at the Macao Running Water Company.
He was among the thousands of viewers at another celebration party
organized by the Macao Federation of Trade Unions.
</P>
<P>
"I feel proud as China wipes out more than one and a half
century of humiliation," he told Xinhua. "I am confident Hong Kong
will have a bright future under the policy of 'one country, two
systems' after its return. And so will Macao."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
