<HEADLINE> Urgent: HKSAR Inauguration, Ceremony Ends (11) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The ceremony for the inauguration of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) and the swearing-in of the HKSAR
Government ended here at 2:04 AM today.
</P>
<P>
Prolonged applause burst from the audience at the ceremony
venue -- the main hall on level seven of the Extension to the Hong
Kong Convention and Exhibition Center -- when Chinese Vice-Premier
Qian Qichen announced the successful conclusion of the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The inauguration ceremony started at 1:30 AM today. At the
beginning of the ceremony, Chinese President Jiang Zemin
proclaimed the establishment of the HKSAR. This was followed by
the swearing-in, separately, of Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of
the HKSAR, 23 principal officials of the HKSAR government, 14
members of the HKSAR Executive Council, members of the HKSAR
Provincial Legislative Council and 34 judges of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng and HKSAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
delivered speeches at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The Central Delegation headed by President Jiang Zemin attended
today's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Attending the ceremony were also more than 4,000
representatives and guests from over 40 countries/regions and over
30 international organizations, all members of a viewing
delegation sent by the interior areas of China, 300
representatives of overseas Chinese and foreigners of Chinese
origin in all parts of the world, personages from Macao and
Taiwan, and people from all walks of life in Hong Kong. Present
were also more than 400 reporters from all parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
With the establishment of the HKSAR and the swearing-in of Tung
Chee Hwa and the HKSAR government composed entirely of local
people, Hong Kong has entered a new era of "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong" after being subjected to 156 years of British
colonial rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
