<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Embraced with Joy for Return to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong was embraced with
overall joyful celebrations Monday for its return to the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
Joy was the word to describe people you met on the streets, in
the
parks and by the banks of the Harbor, just minutes from the
midnight
here on Monday when Hong Kong becomes a special administrative
region
of China.
</P>
<P>
Major celebrations were organized by the local Association for
Celebration of Hong Kong with China (ACHKC), and other regional
organizations and establishments at various sites such as Happy
Valley
in Wanchai, the Cultural Center in Tsim Sha Tsui in Kowloon and
Sheung
Shui in the "new territories".
</P>
<P>
Farmers' drum beating performance raised the curtain of the
celebrations at the horse racing course at Happy Valley, one of
the
two major horse racing courses here.
</P>
<P>
The performance was jointly organized by ACHKC and the Radio
Television Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
And they were followed by dragon and lion dances, which
demonstrated the joy of the local people and the people of China
as
a whole for the end of the more than 150 years of British colonial
rule here.
</P>
<P>
The celebrations also featured such sports stars as China's
Olympic champions Mo Huilan, Li Ning, Wang Yifu, Deng Yaping, Qiao
Hong and Hong Kong artists including Jackey Chan.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Extravaganza '97 with the main stage in the Hong
Kong Cultural Center in Tsim Sha Tsui featured artistic
performance
by some 2,000 artists from both Hong Kong and China's interior
area.
</P>
<P>
Among the performances tonight were a piano concert named "The
Yellow River", the eastward water flow of the river symbolizes the
zigzag course of Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Other artistic pieces were song and dance, acrobatic show and
traditional Chinese dragon dance.
</P>
<P>
The streets of Sheung Shui were all decorated with China's
five-starred national flag and the Hong Kong Special
Administrative
Region flags featuring stars and Bauhinia.
</P>
<P>
A dance party organized by the local organization for Hong
Kong's
handover drew more than 300 people, who stayed for the
count-down for the midnight handover ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"It is a joyful night with historical significance. We gather
together here tonight to usher in the historical moment for Hong
Kong's reunification with the motherland," said Wong Lo-tai, the
spokesman for the organizers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
