<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opium-burning Site Hosts Events Marking Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DONGGUAN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- A century and a half ago, Lin Zexu
burned large quantities of opium confiscated from British traders
in Humen, now under the jurisdiction of Duanguan in south China's
Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Today, the city saw off troops of the People's Liberation Army
who were moving into Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Local people thronged the streets and staged traditional
lion dance to see off the troops leaving the city at midnight.
</P>
<P>
The city had recently hosted a string of activities to welcome
Hong Kong back.
</P>
<P>
Banners, balloons and fireworks adorned the small city and
jubilant people of Dongguan were seen everywhere to express their
excitement by whatever means they thought fit.
</P>
<P>
A gala party was held tonight before the sculptures featuring
opium burning scenes. Local people in nearby towns also staged a
variety of colorful activities to mark the end of 150-year history
of humiliation.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few days, people flocked to a museum on the history of
the Opium War. "The museum received as many as 10,000 visitors
from all over the country,including those from Hong Kong," said
Cheng Xian, deputy curator of the museum. 
</P>
