<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Provisional Legislature Examines Reunification Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is the first of the PLC after the establishment of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
In order to avoid a "legal vacuum", the PLC was convened
immediately after the swearing-in ceremony.
</P>
<P>
At the PLC meeting, Elsie Leung Oi-sie, Secretary of Justice,
is to table the draft Reunification Bill for endorsement.
Published by the Chief Executive's Office, the Bill is intended to
ratify 13 bills which had been passed by the PLC prior to July 1,
1997, and to deal with various transition-related matters.
</P>
<P>
The Bill is to endorse the appointment of judges of the Court
of Final Appeal and the Chief Judge of the High Court. It also
deals with such matters as adaptation of laws, establishment of
courts, continuity of legal proceedings and administration of
justice, continuity of public service, and transfer of government
property.
</P>
<P>
It is the first plenary meeting the PLC has ever held in Hong
Kong since the interim legislature was formed in December 1996.
Over the past six months, the PLC has met in Shenzhen, a southern
China city bordering Hong Kong, and has examined and passed 13
bills, which are indispensable to the establishment of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-nine legislators of the 60-member PLC attended today's
meeting except for Maria Tam Wai-chu, who has resigned since she
was appointed in late June as a member of the first HKSAR Basic
Law Committee under the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
