<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reunification Bill Tabled to HK Provisional Legislature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Secretary of Justice of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) tabled to the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) the draft Hong Kong
Reunification Bill here in the small hours today.
</P>
<P>
The Bill seeks to confirm the 13 bills which have been passed
by the PLC prior to July 1, 1997, and to deal with various
transition-related matters.
</P>
<P>
Elsie Leung Oi-sie presented the bill for three readings at the
PLC's first meeting after the establishment of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), a meeting that started at
2:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
"It is a great privilege for me to be fitting the first bill
into the Council after its formal inauguration earlier this
morning. It is fitting that, on this historic day, the first bill
put before the Council should relate to the reunification of Hong
Kong with the motherland," Leung said.
</P>
<P>
"As a matter both of fact and of law, the reunification has, of
course, been successfully achieved. It is nevertheless desirable
to introduce a number of legislative provisions to facilitate the
smooth transition of the legal system, the administration of
justice, and the public service," she told the legislators.
</P>
<P>
Founded in December 1996, the interim legislature has passed 13
bills, which are indispensable to the establishment of the HKSAR.
These bills cover public holidays, the national flag and national
emblem, the regional flag and regional emblem, provisional
district organizations, the Court of Final Appeal, judicial
service, public order, societies and right of abode.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary of Justice explained to the legislators that the
Bill also aims to endorse the appointment of judges of the Court
of Final Appeal and the Chief Judge of the High Court.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Reunification Bill deals with transition-related
matters such as adaptation of law, establishment of courts,
continuity of legal proceedings and administration of justice,
continuity of public service, and transfer of government property.
</P>
<P>
After the presentation by the Secretary of Justice, the PLC
will go on the first and second readings of the draft
Reunification Bill. Then legislators will immediately have the
second reading debate on the Bill before it goes through the
committee stage and receives the third reading.
</P>
</TEXT>
