<HEADLINE> China: Nationwide Rejoicing at Return of Hong Kong (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Nationwide rejoicing in China
reached a climax at midnight, as tens of millions of people across
the country celebrated the return of Hong Kong with a wide range
of activities, many of which lasted until dawn.
</P>
<P>
The 100,000 people gathered at Tiananmen Square in Beijing
counted down in unison the last 10 seconds of June 30, until the
moment on July 1 when Hong Kong returned to China.
</P>
<P>
Clock-watchers on the square cheered and applauded as they
watched live coverage of the handover ceremony in Hong Kong,
especially when the Union Jack was lowered and the Chinese
national flag raised.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 colored flags are flying in the balmy summer
air here, and thousands of traditional Chinese red lanterns are
hanging over and around the square, where an all-night gala is in
full swing.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai, China's largest economic center, over 10,000
singers gathered along Huangpu River to welcome Hong Kong back
with song.
</P>
<P>
"One hundred years ago, I hopelessly watched you leave; a
century later to celebrate the historic Hong Kong return," they
sang.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, festooned with 800,000 lanterns and two million pots
of flowers, was once forced to lease its port to western
powers. Tonight, thousands of people swarmed onto the streets to
celebrate the historic Hong Kong return.
</P>
<P>
In Shanghai Bund Park, which was set up by British imperialists
and is notorious for a notice board saying "No Chinese and Dogs
Allowed," about 2,500 people sitting in front of the countdown
clock cheered when the city's bell tower struck 12 times.
</P>
<P>
With their excited faces illuminated by fireworks, the people
in the park beat drums, performed a dragon lantern dance and waved
thousands of small flags as they sang the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
In North China's Tianjin city, one million people divided in
60,000 groups joined in a long-distance running today to express
their excitement over the return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
At midnight, with fireworks burst in the sky, people waving
national flags took to the streets dragon dancing and other
traditional Chinese dancing.
</P>
</TEXT>
