<HEADLINE> China: Nationwide Rejoicing at Return of Hong Kong (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, hundreds
of people celebrated the event by joining in a race around the
city. Torch in hand, the joggers formed a moving fire-dragon which
drew applause from spectators along the route.
</P>
<P>
Jinghai Monastery is where the Nanjing Treaty, which led to the
cession of Hong Kong, was negotiated between Qing dynasty
officials and British imperialists.
</P>
<P>
In the temple tonight, the city's mayor struck a giant bell 155
times at midnight amid cheers, symbolizing the end of 155 years of
national humiliation.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou, capital of the prosperous Guangdong Province
adjacent to Hong Kong, was still buzzing with life at this hour of
the night, as thousands of fragrant fresh flowers and bright neon
lights brought residents to the streets for a walk or to take
photos.
</P>
<P>
In the city's Tianhe Stadium, 30,000 people attended a gala
party with singing and dancing which will continue till dawn.
</P>
<P>
The city of Dongguan, where the Chinese launched the resistance
against British invaders by burning large quantities of opium
confiscated from British traders 157 years ago, is awash in a sea
of colorful banners, balloons, flowers and still reverberating
from tonight's fireworks and thundering drumbeats.
</P>
<P>
Five hundred amateur performers are rehearsing for a gala party
at a huge makeshift stage before the sculptures depicting the
burning of opium by General Lin Zexu, a senior Chinese official
from the Qing Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
The people in southwest China's city of Chongqing, which became
China's fourth municipality directly under the Central Government
last month, has one more reason to celebrate. Tonight's
spectacular scene here featured a motorcade of 1,997
locally-produced cars running 10 kilometers through the city's
major streets.
</P>
<P>
When the clock struck twelve, dozens of ships docked at the
Yangzi River blew whistles to greet the Hong Kong homecoming.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, a city in south China's Guangdong Province
neighboring Hong Kong, has been redecorated in recent days with
thousands of flower pots and banners. A total of 100,000
firecrackers, in 1,997 varieties, were set off in 71 separate
launchings during the 70-minute party, the largest celebration
ever held in this special economic zone.
</P>
