<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Enters Into New Era (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
solemnly proclaimed here today: "I hereby declare the
establishment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) of the People's Republic of China."
</P>
<P>
The proclamation was made at the ceremony to mark the
establishment of the HKSAR and the swearing-in of the HKSAR
Government.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR Government, composed entirely of Hong Kong residents
and headed by Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa, was sworn in today,
thus ushering in a new era of "Hong Kong People governing Hong
Kong" after 156 years of British colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
A grand ceremony was held at the extension to the Hong Kong
Convention and Exhibition Center (CEC) to mark this historic
moment. One and half hours ago, the five-star red flag was hoisted
in the CEC, symbolizing the return of Hong Kong to the embrace of
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Hung at the front of the main hall, the venue for the
inauguration and swearing-in ceremony, were a five-star red flag
and the regional flag of the HKSAR featuring a bauhinia. Hundreds
of pots of beautiful flowers before the rostrum increased the
festival atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The hall, which is as large as a football ground, had a full
house at 01:20 AM today. Also present were more than 4,000
representatives and guests from more than 40 countries and regions
and some 30 international organizations, all members of a viewing
delegation from the interior areas of China, 300 representatives
of overseas Chinese and foreigners of Chinese origin in all parts
of the world, persons from Macao and Taiwan, and people from all
walks of life in Hong Kong, who were still in high spirits after
attending the handover ceremony.
</P>
<P>
In the rear of the main hall were more than 400 journalists
from various media organizations across the world. They put up
over 10 TV transmission booths, 12 TV transmission rooms and 13
radio transmission booths to broadcast live this historic event to
an estimated two billion viewers around the world.
</P>
<P>
Walking into the main hall, amid warm applause, were President
Jiang Zemin, who is also general secretary of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China, (CPC) and chairman of
the Central Military Commission (CMC); Li Peng, premier of the
State Council; Qian Qichen, vice premier; Wang Hanbin, vice
chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress; Zhang Wannian, CMC vice chairman; and Tung Chee Hwa,
chief executive of the HKSAR. They were seated in the front row on
the rostrum. Other members of the central delegation also took
seats on the rostrum.
</P>
<P>
At 01:30 AM, Chinese Vice-Premier Qian Qichen announced the
opening of the ceremonies for the inauguration of the HKSAR and of
the swearing-in of the HKSAR Government. All present stood up and
the military band played the national anthem of the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Enters into New Era (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
After the national anthem was played, President Jiang Zemin
proclaimed, in a solemn manner and sonorous voice, "I hereby
declare the establishment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region of the people's Republic of China." This drew a long and
thunderous applause from the audience.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that the concept of "one country, two systems"
put forward by late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping has become a
reality.
</P>
<P>
Then, members of the HKSAR Government began to be sworn in.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, the first chief executive of the HKSAR, walked
to the rostrum and, facing the national flag and the regional flag
and raising his right hand, swore: "I, upon assuming the office of
the Chief Executive of the HKSAR, pledge to uphold the Basic Law
of the HKSAR of the PRC, fulfill my duties wholeheartedly, abide
by laws, be clean and honest, serve the HKSAR, and be responsible
for the PRC and the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Premier Li Peng supervised the process, shook hands
with Tung and congratulated him on his assumption of office.
</P>
<P>
Then, the swearing-in of the 23 principal officials of the
HKSAR was also supervised by Premier Li Peng. Tung Chee Hwa
supervised the swearing-in of the 14 Executive Council members, 59
members of the Provisional Legislative Council and 34 judges.
</P>
<P>
Administrative Secretary Chan Fang On-sang led the principal
officials in the swearing-in. Most of these officials had held
posts in the Brutish Hong Kong Government. As representatives of
the 180,000 civil servants in Hong Kong, the retention of their
posts for the HKSAR has been regarded as an indication of Hong
Kong's smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
The swearing-in of the members of the Executive Council was led
by Chung Sze-Yuen, convener of the Executive Council, while that
of the Provisional Legislative Council was led by its president
Rita Fan Hsu Lai-tai.
</P>
<P>
The executive and legislative departments of the HKSAR are
composed entirely of Hong Kong residents. This reflects the
implementation of the policy of "Hong Kong people governing Hong
Kong."
</P>
<P>
Led by Chief Justice Li Kwok-nang, judges of the HKSAR were
sworn in. This demonstrates that the HKSAR enjoys independent
judicial power, including that of final adjudication.
</P>
<P>
The swearing-in was followed by a speech made by Premier Li
Peng.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the return of Hong Kong to the motherland and the
establishment of the Government of HKSAR mark the successful
application of Deng Xiaoping's great vision of "one country, two
system" in resolving the question of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
They represent an immense success of the Chinese people in
their pursuit for complete national reunification. At the same
time, they are a major contribution to the cause of universal
peace and progress, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has now entered a new historic era and its future will
be even more splendid, Li said. His speech drew a warm applause
from the audience.
</P>
<P>
The policy address of Tung Chee Hwa expressed full confidence
in Hong Kong's future.
</P>
<P>
He said that he will perform, in great dedication, the sacred
duty of a high degree of autonomy in Hong Kong as entrusted by law
and lead the pioneering Hong Kong people on their march along the
road of "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
the 32-minute ceremony ended amid music and applause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
