<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - Backgrounder: HK Provisional Legislative Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) held its first meeting after the establishment of the
HKSAR in the small hours today.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Reunification Bill, which provides for the
confirmation of the 13 bills adopted by the PLC in the six months
before Hong Kong's handover and addresses other transition-related
matters, is expected to be adopted at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The provisional legislature was elected in the southern China
city of Shenzhen on December 21, 1996 by a 400-strong Selection
Committee, which was also responsible for the selection of the
first Chief Executive of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-three of the 60 PLC members served on the last
Legislative Council under the British Hong Kong government while
11 were permanent Hong Kong residents with no Chinese citizenship
or with right of abode in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
The setting up of the PLC was made necessary after the British
side unilaterally pushed ahead with the so-called "political
package" and derailed the "through train".
</P>
<P>
The "through train" means that members of the last Legislative
Council produced by the British Hong Kong authorities in 1995 may
become members of the first Legislative Council of the HKSAR after
going through specified legal procedures if the composition of
this last Legislative Council is in conformity with the relevant
decision of China's National people's Congress (NPC) and the
relevant provisions of the Basic Law and if its members meet
certain requirements.
</P>
<P>
However, the "political package" put forward by Hong Kong
Governor Chris Patten tampered with the means of election by
functional constituencies and by an election committee. As a
result, the composition of the 1995 Legislative Council was not in
conformity with the relevant provisions of the Basic Law and its
members cannot board the "through train" to form the first
Legislative Council of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances, there should be a provisional
legislature to avoid a legal vacuum.
</P>
<P>
According to a decision made by the Preparatory Committee for
the HKSAR on the establishment of the PLC, seven major tasks were
laid out for the provisional legislature, including enacting laws
indispensable to the normal operation of the HKSAR, and revising
and abrogating laws if necessary; examining and approving the
transitional budget; and approving the appointment of the judges
of the Court of Final Appeal and the Chief Justice of the High
Court of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The PLC will stop functioning when the first Legislative
Council of the HKSAR is established, not later than June 30, 1998,
according to the decision.
</P>
<P>
The first plenary meeting of the PLC was held in Shenzhen on
January 25, with Rita Fan elected President of the interim body.
From then on, a total of 12 meetings were held in the southern
China city bordering Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The PLC proved its worth by examining and passing a total of 13
bills since early May.
</P>
<P>
These are the Holidays (1997 and 1998) Bill, the Urban Council
(Amendment) Bill 1997, the Regional Council (Amendment) Bill 1997,
the District Boards (Amendment) Bill 1997, the Legislative Council
Commission (Amendment) Bill 1997, the National Flag and National
Emblem Bill, the Regional Flag and Regional Emblem Bill, the
Public Order (Amendment) Bill 1997, the Societies (Amendment) Bill
1997, the Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal (Amendment) Bill 1997,
the Judicial Service Commission (Amendment) Bill 1997, the
Immigration (Amendment)(No.3) Bill 1997, and the Oaths and
Declarations (Amendment) Bill 1997.
</P>
<P>
These bills, which are believed to be vital to the smooth
operation of the HKSAR, have to be ratified and signed by the
Chief Executive to become HKSAR laws.
</P>
<P>
Three motions were endorsed during pre-handover meetings in
support of the transitional budget, the appointment of Andrew Li
Kwok-nang as the Chief Justice of the HKSAR Court of Final Appeal
(CFA), and the appointment of three permanent judges of the CFA
and the Chief Judge of the High Court.
</P>
<P>
After July 1, the PLC will focus on the election method for the
first Legislative Council of the HKSAR, as PLC President Rita Fan
put it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
