<HEADLINE> Return of Hong Kong To Console Soul of Patriot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xi'an, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The return of Hong Kong to the
motherland was ceremoniously celebrated by descendants of a
patriot in northwest China's Shaanxi province tonight.
</P>
<P>
The event is of special significance for the descendants of a
prime minister of the Qing Dynasty named Wang Ding, who committed
suicide in 1842 to protest the government's shameful decision to
cede Hong Kong to Britain after the loss of the Opium War.
</P>
<P>
Wang Ding was also perceptive in that he went all out to advise
the emperor not to dismiss from post Lin Zexu, the national hero
who courageously imposed a ban on opium trade with Britain.
</P>
<P>
"The soul of Wang Ding could now be comforted now that Hong
Kong is returned....And I hope that future generations could learn
from him and love our country deeply," said one of Wang's
descendents, who donated Wang's former residence to the country
for the building of a memorial hall. 
</P>
