<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-30 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish New Government Vows to Restore Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The newly formed Turkish
government today vowed to safeguard and revive the fundamental
principles of the secular republic.
</P>
<P>
A four-page protocol was disclosed by Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz at a news conference in parliament shortly after his
cabinet list was approved by President Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
The document stressed that Turkey's secularism and democracy
must be respected and safeguarded completely.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the country's secularism has been the
focus of tension between the military and former pro-Islamic Prime
Minister Necmettin Erbakan, who was forced to step down on June 18.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military and some opposition parties have been
accusing Erbakan and his Welfare Party (RP) of supporting rapidly
expanding fundamentalist force, which was regarded as the most
dangerous threat to the country.
</P>
<P>
The protocol also stated that the coalition partners would do
their utmost to stop the society's moral decay, to bring about
the revival of "a clean society" and to rebuild the people's
confidence in the state.
</P>
<P>
It said that immunity of parliamentarians would be restricted
and obstacles preventing the effective battle against corruption
would be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Local English newspaper Daily News said that the Yilmaz
government was extremely possible to launch a judicial
investigation into the corruption charges against Tansu Ciller,
chairwoman of the True Path Party (DYP).
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties have tried to bring Ciller, also deputy
prime minister of the Erbakan-led coalition government, to a
Supreme Court trial for alleged financial scandals, but their
efforts failed due to the RP protection.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz, leader of the Turkish Motherland Party (ANAP) who
formed the country's 55th government, told reporters that he
believed the newly-established government would overcome the
current difficulties with the support of the Turkish peoples.
</P>
<P>
He succeeded in forming the new government thanks to the
support of secular bloc -- the Democratic Left Party, Republican
People's Party and Democratic Turkey Party.
</P>
<P>
As of Sunday, the ANAP-led alliance enjoys 278 votes in the
550-seat parliament with two vacancies, and the RP-DYP alliance
has 270 seats in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that at present Yilmaz and his alliance
would have no difficulty in winning a vote of confidence which was
expected to take place in two weeks at the latest.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan resigned under pressure from both the military and
other secularists and then failed to persuade President Demirel to
appoint DYP leader Ciller to form a new government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Holds Night-long Carnival To Welcome Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The whole nation opened its heart
to welcome Hong Kong home with a dusk-to-dawn celebration on the
Tiananmen Square in central Beijing tonight.
</P>
<P>
Well into the night, the crowd of 100,000 hailed, applauded and
danced as the inauguration ceremony of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) government was beamed through five
huge TV screens on the square.
</P>
<P>
"The ceremony fully demonstrated solemnity of a legitimate
government of the HKSAR," said Jin Xiaoyue, a 26-year-old worker
of neighborhood service.
</P>
<P>
"My colleagues and I never doubt that Hong Kong will have a
brighter future under the HKSAR government," he said.
</P>
<P>
The celebration began at 10:00 this evening.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Mayor Jia Qinglin said at the beginning of the
celebration that Beijing citizens will go all out to support
prosperity and stability in Hong Kong and will join hands with the
Hong Kong people to create a more beautiful future.
</P>
<P>
Tiananmen square was ablaze with hundreds of floodlights and
red lanterns for the biggest festivity in the century tonight. The
square is decorated with 30,000 pots of flowers and the trees
around the square are festooned with colorful lights.
</P>
<P>
"I told my students a lot about Hong Kong's past. But today, a
new page of history is unrolling before our eyes," said Xu Yanqin,
a middle school history teacher.
</P>
<P>
At about midnight, dozens of men, each with a red scarf wrapped
around his head, beat huge drums while 1,997 displays of fireworks
emblazoned the summer sky. The crowd of 100,000 counted down in
unison the last 10 seconds of British colonial rule in the east.
</P>
<P>
At zero hour of July 1, they watched the raising of the Chinese
national flag in Hong Kong televised by five huge screens on the
square, singing the Chinese national anthem.
</P>
<P>
"The nation's fate has been totally changed," said Ma Lin, a
worker from a steel company in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Ancient emperors living in the Forbidden City beside this
square closed the doors of China, but failed to stop Britain to
seize Hong Kong from the country. Today, we resumed the exercise
of sovereignty over Hong Kong because China has become more open
and stronger," he said.
</P>
<P>
The celebration is still going on with the crowd dancing in big
circles around the square.
</P>
<P>
"I feel exited to have the opportunity to witness Hong Kong
comes back to the embrace of the motherland on this square in
Beijing," said Xu, a Hong Kong businessman who flew into here from
Hong Kong to attend the celebrating activities.
</P>
<P>
"I have full confidence in the future of Hong Kong, because the
Special Administrative Region will be run under the guideline
of 'one country, two systems' that Mr. Deng Xiaoping put forward,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The celebration will end at about 5:00 this morning as the
national flag is raised on the square. 
</P>
</TEXT>
