<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Return Moves San Francisco Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Overseas Chinese here were
overexcited today when they watched TV programs that Hong Kong was
officially returned to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
"The day has finally come after 150 years of British rule,"
said Wei Xuxun, a 67-year-old retiree in San Francisco. "My wife
and I got up early this morning and were watching the live TV
broadcasting of the handover ceremony. When we saw the national
flag of China flying aloft in Hong Kong, we moved into tears."
</P>
<P>
He said that it was one of the greatest event in the century.
Hong Kong's return from the British control to China marks the
prosperity of the motherland. "As overseas Chinese, we are proud
of Hong Kong's return. We believe in the bright future of China,
including Hong Kong." he added.
</P>
<P>
Wei is one of the some 300,000 overseas Chinese in the San
Francisco Bay area. Various celebrations, including dancing
parties, theatrical performances, art and photo exhibitions, were
held in the last few weeks here to mark the event. Chinatown in
the city has been decorated with national flag of China, the flag
of Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, banners and balloons.
</P>
<P>
"This is the moment the three generations of our family have
expected," said Zhong Zhilan, 65, director of the Institute of
Oriental Art in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
She said that her grandfather, who was a businessmen in Japan,
had supported Dr. Sun Yat-sen's revolution all his life. He
expressed the confidence that China would prosper and Hong Kong
would return to the motherland in his final days. Her father had
lived in Britain and Hong Kong for over six decades. He returned
to hometown in Guangdong Province soon after New China was
founded. Before he died of disease in 1966, he expressed the
regret that he could not see Hong Kong's return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
"Their wish has finally come true. This is the happiest event
in my life," Zhong added.
</P>
<P>
Adrew Lee, president of Laser Discovery, said that he and other
Hong Kong people here felt that the orphan had returned to the
family of motherland. In the future, he believed that Hong Kong
and other parts of China would cooperate more closely and make a
better play of strength and advantages each other, and Hong Kong's
economy would develop in a greater space.
</P>
<P>
After watching the live broadcasting, Chinese Students in San
Francisco Bay area voluntarily held group discussions, talking
about how to make contributions to development of Hong Kong and
other parts of China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
