<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Industry Confident in Hong Kong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- German industry today expressed
confidence in the future of Hong Kong after its return to China.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued by Germany's umbrella
organization of chambers of commerce, DIHT, the confidence was
confirmed by a DIHT survey showing that half of the some 250
German companies now active in Hong Kong are planning to expand
their business activities there in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The German Federation for Wholesale and Foreign Trade (BGA)
Monday also said that it sees no adverse effects of Hong Kong's
return. Commercial business there is expected to keep growing,
said BGA president Michael Fuchs.
</P>
<P>
Official figures showed that the number of German companies
with subsidiaries in Hong Kong has increased by 20 percent since
1990. Hong Kong is now the seventh-largest trading partner with
Germany with a trade volume of 10 billion U.S. dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
Heinrich v. Pierer, head of Germany's largest electronics
company Siemens, today also voiced confidence in Hong Kong's
future.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Pierer said that the success of
Hong Kong is based on a liberal economic system, and the
flexibility as well as the enterpreneurship of its population
which can be now combined with the economic expansion of the
mainland. "There emerges an additional potential," he added.
</P>
<P>
Pierer, who is also chairman of the Asian-Pacific Committee of
German Economy, noted that Hong Kong's return will also certainly
further deepen the existing close trade and economic relations
between China and Germany.
</P>
<P>
According to Pierer, Siemens has managed to achieve an average
annual growth rate of 40 percent in the past 10 years in Hong Kong
and is planning to expand its presence there in the belief that
its business with Chinese firms in Hong Kong and with the
surrounding areas will expand further. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
