<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. to Create Observer Mission in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council today voted unanimously to close its current peacekeeping
operation and create an observer mission in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The observer mission, including 86 lightly-armed military
officers and 345 civilian police, will begin its operation on July
1.
</P>
<P>
The former U.N. Angola Verification Mission, set up in 1995,
will withdraw slowly from the country.
</P>
<P>
The Verification Mission was set up to help implement the
agreement signed in Lusaka, Zambia, in November 1994 that ended
nearly two decades of civil war in the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
"After a long and difficult path, the Lusaka protocol has
finally entered its final stage," Afonso van Dunem Mbinda,
Angola's representative to the United Nations, told the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xuexian, China's Deputy Permanent Representative to the
United Nations, said at the Council meeting that the Chinese
government was pleased at the positive momentum of the Angolan
peace process, but was concerned at the recent outbreaks of
violence in northern Angola.
</P>
<P>
The dawn of peace was on the horizon, and the Angolan
government and UNITA should seize the opportunity of achieving the
remaining tasks in the political field, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China supported the establishment of the U.N.
observer mission in the belief that it would promote national
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
But, as a principle, the Security Council should not get
involved in those activities which fall under the terms of
reference of other U.N. bodies, the Chinese Deputy Representative
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
