<HEADLINE> June 30: Memory of a Lifetime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- As both hands of the clock pointed
to twelve at midnight on June 30, over 10,000 students and
teachers in China's Qinghua University jumped from their seats and
sang in chorus the national anthem as they were watching the
five-star red flag being raised in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Like the rest university campuses all over China, Qinghua held
night-long celebrations to greet Hong Kong's homecoming to the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
Students and teachers gathered in front of a large-screen TV
in the school's auditorium, awaiting the historic moment.
</P>
<P>
They cheered and applauded a number of special onscreen moments
when China's guard of honor appeared, when Chinese President Jiang
Zemin took his place on the stage at the handover ceremony on
behalf of the Chinese government, and when the national flag was
raised.
</P>
<P>
Qinghua's festivities started at 8 p.m. with a presentation of
the new movie "The Opium War," the most expensive movie made in
China, detailing the events that led up to the cession of Hong
Kong to Britain. At 11 p.m., the crowd sang "A Pearl in the East,"
a song dedicated to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"This is a night that we can never forget," said Liang Youneng,
vice-president of Qinghua.
</P>
<P>
Qinghua and the new Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
share the same symbol -- the bauhinia flower.
</P>
<P>
"We young people have the confidence and capabilities in making
Hong Kong as well as the motherland more prosperous and stronger
in the future," said Zhang Shihong, who is working for a master's
degree in human studies.
</P>
<P>
Beijing University, a neighbor of Qinghua, opened 25 spots for
students to watch the evening's activities on TV.
</P>
<P>
The "May 4th Playground" attracted the biggest crowd: more than
3,000 students, either sitting on the ground or standing shoulder
to shoulder, watched the ceremony in Hong Kong in front of a TV
with a screen measuring eight meters high and 5.5 meters wide.
</P>
<P>
Wu Tingyao, a junior majoring in electronics, lit two candles
to express his best wishes for Hong Kong's future. "Hong Kong's
return makes all Chinese feel proud and elated," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hou Renzhi, 85, a geo-historian of Beijing University, and an
academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said, "I am very
excited that I can see the day coming up after having waited for
nearly one century."
</P>
<P>
"Deep sorrow leads to enlightment, and catastrophe rejuvenates
a country," he expressed his emotions at the moment, borrowing an
expression from his ancestors.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's return is only a beginning," Hou said. "Even
greater moment is yet to come, when compatriots across the
Taiwan Straits eventually reunite."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
