<HEADLINE> Cypriot, Greek Leaders Urge Cooperation on Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis today stressed
the need for closer cooperation between the two countries on the
Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
After a two-hour meeting with Simitis, Clerides said his
government would hold direct talks with Turkish-Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash with "good intentions", but it is determined to
protect the just causes and interests of the island.
</P>
<P>
Simitis told reporters that the first-yet direct talks between
the two sides on Cyprus would lead to "a just and viable solution"
to the Cyprus problem under United Nations resolutions and
decisions taken at community summits in 1977 and 1989 respectively.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the initiatives being undertaken aimed at seeking
solutions to the issue, which were within the framework set by
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Simitis said that Cyprus' entry into the European
Union (EU) could help improve the settlement of the Cyprus problem
because the solutions being pursued should be compatible with
European principles.
</P>
<P>
Clerides, who arrived here Monday for a visit to Greece, is
consulting with Greek leaders ahead of his forthcoming talks with
Denktash in New York on July 9.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops occupied
the northern part of the island following a coup plotted by the
then ruling junta in Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
