<HEADLINE> One Street, Two Systems: HK and Shenzhen Residents Celebrate Return of HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Residents on both sides of Chung
Ying Street, the middle line of which served as the boundary
between China's inland area and Hong Kong's New Territories,
celebrated their reunion today.
</P>
<P>
People in Shatoujiao Town, where the street is located, had
been living in two separate areas since the Convention Respecting
An Extension of the Hong Kong Territory was signed in 1898.
</P>
<P>
Today, the long winding street was decorated with colorful
lights and lanterns and scores of the Chinese national flag and
the flag of Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) were
hung up and down the street.
</P>
<P>
Early this morning, more than 300 people in Shatoujiao Village
of Hong Kong's New Territories crossed Chung Ying in the rain to
enter the city of Shenzhen in South China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
One of the villagers, surnamed Lee, told reporters that he was
pleased about Hong Kong's return. "Though the street will remain
divided, we will be like one family, running businesses and
seeking development together," he said.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 Hong Kong and Shenzhen people paraded along the
street, waving miniatures of the Chinese five-star flag and the
flag of HKSAR, and beating gongs and drums. Some of them performed
lion and dragon dances.
</P>
<P>
The dance of the Chinese unicorn, staged under a big fig tree
to symbolize that the Hong Kong and Shenzhen people have the same
roots, was warmly received by the audience.
</P>
<P>
"We are like two melons growing on the same vine," said Liu
Weiqiang, head of a neighborhood committee on Zhongxing Street in
Shenzhen, referring to Hong Kong and Shenzhen people. "We should
help and take care of each other and build our hometown together."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
