<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Makes New WTO Offer on Financial Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) made a
new offer today to the World Trade Organization (WTO) in Geneva as
part of its drive to bring about a global deal to open financial
services markets by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The new proposal, adopted by trade officials from EU member
states, includes eliminating 12 residual restrictions and reducing
nine others in Austrian banking, the Amsterdam stock exchange and
Portuguese investment funds among other areas.
</P>
<P>
The offer to increase the scope of the EU's market opening in
financial services is aimed at spurring other WTO members to
improve their commitments to the financial services market.
</P>
<P>
The EU expected the other WTO countries to grant real market
access opportunities to foreign financial institutions by July
14, the pre-agreed date for revised offers.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the EU is trying to inject momentum into the WTO
talks well in time for a global deal by the December deadline set
by the WTO two years ago.
</P>
<P>
The EU's financial services market represents more than 25
percent of the world's insurance, banking and share trading
markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
