<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Called for "No Conditions" on Payment of Dues to UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has been urged to insist that the U.S. Senate's 38 conditions
precluding payment of American dues to the United Nations be
stripped from the foreign affairs authorization bill in the
upcoming House-Senate Conference Committee.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made in a strongly worded letter to Clinton at
the end of last month by John C. Whitehead, chairman of the U.N.
Association of the USA, and Ellitot Richardson, co-chairman of the
Association's National Council, according to a press release of
the association available today.
</P>
<P>
"We urge you to use the power of the Presidency, publicly and
forcefully, to reverse the dangerous direction of Congressional
debate," the two former U.S. statesmen said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. House version of the bill makes no provision for
payment of the 1.6 billion dollars the U.S. owes in arrears to the
world body and other international agencies.
</P>
<P>
However, the Senate bill, sponsored by Republican hardliner
Jesse Helms, authorizes payment of up to 819 million U.S. dollars
in arrears over the next two years. It stipulates that the United
Nations must first meet dozens of conditions.
</P>
<P>
These conditions of repayment include a write off of nearly
half of the U.S. debt to a dormant account and reduction of the
U.S. share of U.N. expenses from 25 percent to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
The two statesmen said that many of the ideas found in the
legislation are "ill-conceived," particularly the unilateral
demand fro reduction in the U.S. rate of assessment, which would
force the other member states to add a fifth of America's share to
their own U.N. assessment.
</P>
<P>
They also regarded unacceptable the requirement that 5 percent
of U.N. professional staff positions remain vacant.
</P>
<P>
They expressed the fear that these provisions "will cast a long
shadow over our conduct of multilateral diplomacy as well as
undercut our leadership at the United Nations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
