<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Day of HKSAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- When the Chinese national flag
and the regional bauhinia flag of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) were hoisted at zero hour today,
Hong Kong started a new day and a new era.
</P>
<P>
At the stroke of midnight, police officers on duty in the Hong
Kong Convention and Exhibition Center, the venue for Hong Kong's
handover ceremony, replaced their colonial police insignia with a
new insignia featuring bauhinia. Reporters from inland areas and
Hong Kong exchanged greetings, saying "we are of the same family."
</P>
<P>
Countless people stayed the night to watch the handover
ceremony, to wait for the moment that Hong Kong became part of
China again, and to greet the first day of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
On the Hong Kong Island, the bright illumination in the
Convention Center lit up the Victoria Harbor; in Kowloon, the
3.5-km-long dragon formed by lights extended from Tsim Sha Tsui
way up to the Border Street; and in "New Territories", tens of
thousands of people thronged to the junction with Shenzhen to
welcome the arrival of the People's Liberation Army troops to be
stationed in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
When morning came, people swarmed to newsstands to buy
newspapers, all covering extensively the handover activities. In
front of the General Post Office on the Hong Kong Island, hundreds
of people queued for a set of commemorative stamps and envelopes.
</P>
<P>
Although today is the fourth of a five-day public holiday, the
subway was even crowded than rush hours on working days. A
commemorative ticket costing only 25 HK dollars enables people to
travel an unlimited mileage in Hong Kong's extension subway
network, called the Mass Transit Railways, within today.
</P>
<P>
In the square in Central, Hong Kong's downtown area, people were
having pictures taken in front of a commemorative pavilion for
Hong Kong's return to China. More lens were focused on the red
five-star flag, the Chinese national flag, and the bauhinia flag
of the HKSAR, which were hoisted for the first time in the
building housing Hong Kong's legislature.
</P>
<P>
A young couple taking pictures caught the attention of
passers-by, for wearing T-shirts with the words "Hello, China" on
the front, and "Good bye, Britain" on the back.
</P>
<P>
In a shop selling magazines and souvenirs on the Theatre Lane
in Central, Lo Hoi and his two assistants were busy receiving
people coming to buy the national and regional flags.
</P>
<P>
"Most people want national flags, and they prefer larger ones.
How many have we sold? I really cannot tell," said Lo, who owns
the Ah Lo Magazines Co., while busy taking flags for customers.
</P>
<P>
At nine o'clock in the evening, hundreds of thousands of people
flocked to both banks of the Victoria Harbor to watch Hong Kong
'97 Spectacular, a gala show with music, fountains, laser,
decorated boats, and fireworks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
