<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin's 20 Hours in Hong Kong (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The presence of the Chinese government delegation led by Jiang
Zemin at the Hong Kong handover ceremony at the midnight of June
30 attracted worldwide attention. An estimated two billion people
watched the ceremony via live TV broadcast. At zero hour of July
1, the five-star red flag was raised at the venue of the ceremony
and Jiang Zemin proclaimed to the world China's resumption of the
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"July 1, 1997, will go down in the annals of history as a day
that merits eternal memory. The return of Hong Kong to the
motherland after going through more than a century of vicissitudes
indicates that from now on, Hong Kong compatriots have become true
masters of this Chinese land and that Hong Kong has now entered a
new era of development."
</P>
<P>
At 1:32 am, Jiang Zemin announced the establishment of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) of the People's
Republic of China at the ceremony for the inauguration of the
HKSAR of the PRC and the swearing-in of the HKSAR government. This
was followed by the swearing-in of the HKSAR government composed
entire of Hong Kong people. The "one country, two sytems" concept
has become a reality.
</P>
<P>
Before the handover, President Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng
met with more than 80 foreign dignitaries who had come to attend
the Hong Kong handover ceremony and celebrations.
</P>
<P>
It was 2:30 am when Jiang Zemin met officials of the HKSAR
government who had just been sworn in. Up to then, the Chinese
president had spent the first ten busy hours in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
At 10 am, July 1, Jiang went again to the Extension to the Hong
Kong Convention and Exhibition Center, where he attended a grand
celebration for the establishment of the HKSAR. This was the first
time a top Chinese leader joined Hong Kongers in a joyous
celebration.
</P>
<P>
At the celebration, the Chinese president extended his
congratulations to Mr Tung Chee Hwa on his assumption of office as
HKSAR Chief Executive. "We have full confidence in the HKSAR
government under his leadership and will give it full support," he
said.
</P>
<P>
At 1:05 pm, President Jiang Zemin boarded his plane and flew
back to Beijing after spending 20 busy hours in Hong Kong. In
Beijing, the national capital, a grand celebration attended by
80,000 people was waiting for him.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin's 20 Hours in Hong Kong (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
left here for Beijing this afternoon after a 20-hour whirlwind
visit to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In the past 20 hours, Jiang, who is also general secretary of
the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and
chairman of the Central Military Commission, led the Chinese
government delegation for attendance to the Hong Kong handover
ceremony and the Central Delegation for attendance to the ceremony
for the inauguration of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) of the People's Republic of China and the
swearing-in of the HKSAR government.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, together with Premier Li Peng, met with the Prince of
Wales and Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain and more than 80
other foreign dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
The special airplanes carrying the Chinese government
delegation led by Jiang Zemin touched down at the Kai Tak
International Airport at 5:05 pm on June 30. They were greeted by
hundreds of people representing all walks of life in Hong Kong,
who stood in the rain and held the national flag of China and the
regional flag of the HKSAR. Some 150 Chinese and foreign reporters
had arrived at designated areas hours before the arrival of the
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin and Li Peng descended from the ramps at 5:28 with
smiles. This represented a historic moment: it was the first time
in history that China's top leader set his foot in this part of
Chinese territory subjected to British colonial rule for 156
years.
</P>
<P>
The cause of bringing Hong Kong back to the embrace of the
motherland has involved the incessant struggles of the Chinese
people and painstaking efforts of three generations of Chinese
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Prior to departure from Beijing, Jiang said, "We should bear in
mind the great achievements made by the late Chinese leaders Mao
Zedong, Zhou Enlai and Deng Xiaoping."
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Hong Kong, Jiang expressed on various
occasions that he cherished the memories of Deng Xiaoping, who put
forward the great concept of "one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with British Prime Ministry Tony Blair at 8:20
pm, Jiang said Chinese and British leaders should "stand high and
look forward" and view Sino-British relations from a strategic
point of view geared to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
When he met Prince Charles before the handover ceremony, Jiang
expressed the Chinese Government's confidence and determination in
 implementing the policies of "one country, two systems" and "Hong
Kong people governing Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
When he met with foreign dignitaries or made speeches during
his stay in Hong Kong, Jiang stressed, time and again, that the
policy of "one country, two systems" is not an expedient measure
but a decision that has been made with China's overall national
interests taken into account. He reiterated at the HKSAR
inauguration ceremony that this basic policy will remain unchanged
for 50 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
