<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somalis Condemn Military Court Decision in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The main factions in the Somali
capital have today reacted strongly to the decisions made by the
military court in Belgium which acquitted two soldiers who
committed human rights violations in Somalia during their stay
with the United Nations troops in the southern port town of
Kismaio.
</P>
<P>
Hussein Sheikh Ahmed Kadare, press secretary of Ali Mahdi's
faction, said the acquittal made by the Brussels court was a real
degradation of the Somali people and the Muslims in general and a
major violation to the international laws.
</P>
<P>
Kadare said, anger has incited them when they heard the
reasoning of the judge in the court who freed the two men on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The secretary has proposed that the case of those soldiers be
taken to a neutral court in a neutral country with the presence
of Muslim scholars and judges.
</P>
<P>
The military court decision was also criticized and condemned
by the faction led by Hussein Mohamed Aidid who called on all
international human rights organizations and those who advocate
for the rights of the children to condemn the Belgian legal
administration.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Qanyare Afrah, interior secretary of Hussein Aidid's
government, said the decision by the Belgian court shows the
persistence of white people's discrimination against the black.
</P>
<P>
Afrah said the Belgian soldiers have not only violated the
prestige of the Somalis, but the Muslim religion and the culture
of the Somalis as well.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, large demonstrations were held today in several
parts of the war torn capital, Mogadishu, marking the 37th
anniversary when the southern regions of Somalia took their
independence from the Italian colony, who joined the northern
regions colonized by Britain in 1960.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of cheering people have gathered in Mogadishu's main
stadium today singing and dancing traditional folklore dances,
blowing horns and beating drums.
</P>
<P>
"It is now time when the Somalis forget the use of arms and
settle their differences through peaceful ways without the
intervention of foreigners," Hussein Mohamed Aidid told the
crowd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
