<HEADLINE> Macao Editorials Hail Hong Kong's Return to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Leading Chinese newspapers in Macao
today carried editorials, hailing the return of Hong Kong to China
as a "major event both for China and the entire world."
</P>
<P>
The Macao Daily News, the number one newspaper in Macao, said
in an editorial in an extra published early in the morning that
Hong Kong's return marks a new beginning for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's return to China is the success of Deng Xiaoping's
great concept of "one country, two systems," it said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it said that people should also commemorate the
national heroes who fought against foreign invasions since the
Opium War (1840-1842).
</P>
<P>
The Va Kio newspaper said in a frontpage editorial that Hong
Kong will enjoy a better future after China resumes its exercise
of sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The editorial also said that Hong Kong's return and the
establishment of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) have far-reaching significance.
</P>
<P>
The Tai Chung Pou newspaper said that Hong Kong's return has
broad and far-reaching significance in five aspects: that China
gets rid of humiliation, that the policy of "one country, two
systems" achieves success, that Hong Kong began to enter a new
era, that China has taken an important step in its reunification
cause and that Hong Kong's return is a success of the people of
the whole people in anti-colonialism.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some editorials pointed out that Hong Kong's return
will have a positive impact on Macao, which will also return to
China in two and half years under the same policy of "one country,
two systems."
</P>
<P>
"What happened in Hong Kong today will happen in Macao
tomorrow," the editorial in the Va Kio newspaper said. "Macao can
learn a lot from Hong Kong, such as in the preparation for the
Hong Kong SAR."
</P>
<P>
It added that Macao still needs to do much for a smooth
handover of power in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"The Macao government should step up the process of the
localization of civil service, of law and the use of Chinese as an
official language. And the work on the transfer of archives and
government assets should be started as soon as possible," it said,
adding, "The Basic Law of Macao should also be known by more
people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
