<HEADLINE> Chinese Embassies in L.America Celebrate Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese embassies and consulates in
Mexico and Chile hosted receptions and exhibitions Monday, marking
Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to Mexico, Shen Yunao, held a reception in
the embassy, celebrating China's resumption of the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong on midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
About 600 guests, including the president of Mexico's Chamber
of Deputies, Juan Jose Osorio Palacio, the vice president of the
Chamber of Deputies and chairman of the Foreign Affairs
Commission, Augusto Gomez Villanueva, and Mexicans from all walks
of life attended the reception.
</P>
<P>
All the Mexican guests expressed their warmest and heartfelt
congratulations and their joy over Hong Kong's return.
</P>
<P>
They also hoped that Hong Kong and China's inland areas would
be more thriving and prosperous after the handover.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese consulate-general in the northwestern Mexican city
of Tijuana hosted the photo exhibition "Hong Kong Today" in the
city's cultural center.
</P>
<P>
Former Governor of the Lower California State, Roberto de la
Madrid, together with about 500 representatives of
Chinese-Mexicans from Tijuana and neighboring cities of Mexicali
and Ensenada attended the opening ceremony of the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador to Chile Wang Chengjia, also hosted a grand
reception in the embassy, marking China's resumption of the
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
About 800 people attended the reception, including celebrities
such as Vice President of Chile's Chamber of Deputies Jaime Rocha,
Acting Foreign Minister, Minister of Public Works Ricardo Lagos
Escobar, Minister of Planning and Cooperation Roberto Pizarro.
</P>
<P>
At the reception, the celebrities and people from all walks of
life watched the videotape of the ceremony of the transfer of
power in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Wang pointed out that the "one country, two systems" principle
adopted by the Chinese government in solving the Hong Kong issue
will surely be conducive to the fulfillment of the grand cause of
national reunification. 
</P>
</TEXT>
