<HEADLINE> S. Korean NKP Leader Seeks Presidential Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 1 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's ruling New Korea Party
(NKP) Chairman Lee Hoi-chang resigned today to compete with the
other six contenders for presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
After Lee submitted his resignation, President Kim Young-sam,
the president of the NKP, appointed the party's Standing Adviser
Lee Man-sup as new chairman.
</P>
<P>
Lee's resignation, following his declaration on June 20 to bid
for the party's presidential candidate, has brought an end to the
dispute over his step-down.
</P>
<P>
Lee, who became the NKP chairman in March when the nation was
rocked by the Hanbo scandal, was asked earlier to step down to
ensure a fair competition in the nomination race by the six
promising presidential nominees and the party's largest faction,
the Council for Political Development (CPD).
</P>
<P>
The six are former Prime Minister Lee Soo-sung, Provincial
Governor Rhee In-je, lawmaker Kim Deog-ryong, former Seoul mayor
Choe Byung-yul, veteran politician Park Chan-jong, and Lee
Han-dong..
</P>
<P>
The NKP is expected to choose its presidential candidate at a
national convention scheduled for July 21.
</P>
<P>
Joint speech rallies of the contenders, the highlight of the
20-day campaign, will be held in the party's provincial and
municipal chapters on July 5-16. 
</P>
</TEXT>
