<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Peace Makers Killed by Kamajors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 1 (Xinhua)- Three delegates on two peace
missions to urge Kamajor militia-men in the south to abandon
their fight and join the military junta in Sierra Leone in a
broad based government were killed in separate incidents on
Sunday, military sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The first incident occurred in Sengehun village, four miles
from Bo when two of the delegates, university lecturer Joseph
Tommy and a leading businessman Moses Jajah were beheaded by a
group of militiamen. Three other delegates fled into a nearby
forest to escape capture by the Kamajors who branded them as
traitors.
</P>
<P>
The third victim, a security officer of a private agency in
Bo, Philip Bayo was beheaded in Gerihun, 22 miles from Bo when he
attempted to hold a peace meeting with a group of Kamajors on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bayo's body was later dumped in a dustbin, local residents
said.
</P>
<P>
According to observers, this is the third group of peace
makers that had been rebuffed by the Kamajors.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a 10 man delegation went to the north on a similar
mission. Nine of the delegates were seized by the Kamajors and
have not yet been released while the tenth was given a message to
four northern paramount chiefs requesting a meeting with the
Kamajors. The chiefs declined the invitation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bo-Kenema highway blocked by Kamajors for over
three weeks was reopened Monday night after government troops
backed by former rebel combatants overran the barrier, killing 10
Kamajors and losing six soldiers after a three day fighting.
</P>
<P>
The first convoy of commercial vehicles carried essential
consumer items including petroleum products, local residents
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
