<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Celebrate Return of Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's homecoming has been
enthusiastically welcomed by the Chinese people across the country
who have organized non-stop activities to celebrate the historic
event.
</P>
<P>
In Urumqi, the capital city of north China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, some 10,000 people from all walks of life
gathered at the central square this morning to watch the first
raising of the national flag after the return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
At 6:30 a.m., the crowd sang the Chinese national anthem as the
Five-Star Red Flag was raised in the breeze.
</P>
<P>
A spectator in his 50s said that today's flag-raising ceremony
is of special significance, as Hong Kong has finally returned to
the embrace of the motherland and the country has become more
powerful.
</P>
<P>
"As people of the Chinese nation, we all feel very proud and
excited," he said.
</P>
<P>
A 64-year-old man who works in a mosque said, "After watching
the handover ceremony, I feel China has become more powerful and I
feel it is sacred to participate in a flag-raising ceremony on a
special day like today."
</P>
<P>
Among the crowd were 62 pairs of newlyweds who gathered for a
joint wedding ceremony.
</P>
<P>
One couple said they timed their wedding to coincide with the
return of Hong Kong because it is "an honorable and memorable
event."
</P>
<P>
In Zhengzhou, capital of central China's Henan Province, the
main streets and the square were decorated with pots of flowers,
flags, banners and lanterns.
</P>
<P>
As the Chinese national flag was hoisted in Hong Kong, the
people sang and danced.
</P>
<P>
In Jinghua Village of Xinxiang County, the local park was lit
up and lanterns were hung everywhere. Families gathered in front
of the TV to watch the live broadcast of the midnight handover
ceremony in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We are proud that our country is becoming more powerful and
prosperous by the day, and has erased the traces of humiliation of
over 100 years. And we farmers are becoming better-off day by
day," said a 73-year-old man.
</P>
<P>
In central Hunan Province, Shang Qixu, a centenarian who has
been deaf for 20 years, said, "I cannot hear the footsteps of the
homecoming of Hong Kong with my ears, but I can hear it with my
heart."
</P>
<P>
Shang said he still clearly recalls the unfair treatment he
received from foreigners when he participated in a work-study
program 79 years ago. He said that people of a poor, backward
country are subject to humiliation and bullying and they will
regain their pride only after their country becomes more
powerful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
