<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian First Lady Urges Against Spread of AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian first lady, Mrs Vera
Chiluba, has urged people in her country to uphold cultural
values in an effort to halt the spread of the deadly disease of
AIDS, Zambia News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mrs Chiluba who is the chairperson of the Hope Foundation of
Zambia, made the appeal in Chingola during her tour of Hope
Foundation clubs in Copperbelt province on Monday.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the prevalence of HIV/AIDS could be attributed
to people's negative attitude towards cultural values. She said
that modern generation has discarded traditional values like
abstinence from sex by youths, leading to moral decay and the
outbreak of sexually transmitted diseases like AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Mrs Chiluba said that the AIDS pandemic is unfortunately
claiming lives of people still in the prime of their lives.
</P>
<P>
The youths form the bulk of workers in the productive sector
and there would be no meaning for development if they continued
to die from the disease, she added.
</P>
<P>
AIDS is one of the major killer diseases in Zambia. Measures
are on publicity to prevent it from spread particularly among the
youths. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
