<HEADLINE> Compensation Paid to Families of Victims in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced here today that
34.5 million U.S. dollars in compensation has so far been paid
to bereaved families of 143 victims of an Iranian Airbus shot
down by a U.S. warship in the Persian Gulf in 1988.
</P>
<P>
This was made known by Goudarz Eftekhar Jahromi, head of
the International Legal Services Department of Iran's
Presidential Office, on the eve of the 19th anniversary of the
downing of the airliner on July 3, 1988, which killed all the
290 passengers and crew aboard.
</P>
<P>
The Iran Air Airbus en-route to Dubai of the United Arab
Emirates was shot and blown up into pieces in the air by missiles
fired by the U.S. warship of the USS Vincennes shortly after its
take-off from Bandar Abbas in southern Iran.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the latest measures taken to pay compensated money
to the immediate relatives of the victims, the Iranian official
said that relatives of 32 victims have not yet received their
compensation. Necessary measures have been taken to contact them,
he added.
</P>
<P>
On the payment of the compensation to relatives of each victim,
Jahromi said, some 300,000 dollars will be compensated to the
family of each victim who was a bread-winner of the family while
those victims who were not the major supporters, the families
will receive 150,000 dollars each.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the scale of the catastrophe is such that
payment of the compensation would not make up for the disaster.
The United States will always bear the shameful scars of this
hideous act on its face, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
