<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Philippine Situation Under Control: Ramos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said today that the situation in Mindanao, the southern
Philippines, has been put under control and that the Muslim rebels
would return soon to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
He said that "most, if not all, of the civilian hostages" held
last week by the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) rebels have
been released and government agencies have been in place to
provide assistance to dislocated civilians.
</P>
<P>
Reiterating that fears that hostilities between government
troops and the MILF would escalate had no basis, he said the
conflict has been confined to only a few villages in three
provinces in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"The confrontation has died down and again, we are hopeful that
the MILF would resume the peace negotiations," he said.
</P>
<P>
MILF rebels took some 100 bus passengers last week as human
shields against offensives by government troops. After a fierce
fighting, the rebels freed 60 hostages and fled the area of
conflict.
</P>
<P>
At least 100 rebels have been killed since the military
launched an all-out war on June 16 against MILF rebels suspected
of being involved in kidnap activities in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
After the hostage-taking event, the MILF called off its peace
talks slated for June 29-30 with the government. Since earlier
this year, the two sides have held five rounds of preliminary
talks, but made little progress in forging even a full ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a 12,000-member rebel group, broke away in the 1970s
from the Moro National Liberation Front which inked a final peace
agreement with the government last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
