<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Basic Law Committee of NPC Established </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Committee for the Basic Law of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), which will
operate directly under the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress (NPC), was formally established today, NPC
Standing Committee Chairman Qiao Shi announced here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a plenary meeting of the 26th session of the Eighth
NPC Standing Committee, Qiao said that the NPC and its Standing
Committee will follow their duties to the letter to implement the
Basic Law of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
He said the committee has announced names of the 12 appointees
to the Basic Law Committee of HKSAR. Half of them are from Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said he hoped that the new members of the Committee of the
Basic Law of HKSAR also would make their due contributions to
implementing the law, so as to ensure the prosperity and stability
of the region.
</P>
<P>
Qiao also said the tasks of the Basic Law Committee are
studying issues concerning the implementation of Articles 17, 18,
158 and 159 of the Basic Law and offering suggestions to the NPC
Standing Committee in this regard.
</P>
<P>
These articles are on HKSAR's legislative power, the kind of
laws to be in force in the HKSAR, interpretation of the Basic Law,
and the amendment of the Law.
</P>
<P>
After the speech, Qiao presented certificates of appointment to
the new committee members amid thundering applause.
</P>
<P>
The Committee for the Basic Law of the HKSAR of the NPC then
convened a meeting in the newly-built Hong Kong Hall in the Great
Hall of the People, during which members unanimously supported a
proposal to add or delete certain legal stipulations written in
Annex III of the Basic Law regarding national laws to be applied
in the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The decision, which will be released in a separate text, was
adopted by the NPC Standing Committee in a plenary meeting later
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
This afternoon's plenary meeting was chaired by Vice-Chairman
of the NPC Standing Committee Tian Jiyun. After the meeting,
members of the NPC Standing Committee attended activities in
Beijing to celebrate the return of Hong Kong to the
motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Again Urges Israel to Implement UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri reiterated here today his country's demand on Israeli
compliance with U.N. Security Council resolution 425, calling for
Israel's unconditional withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Quoted by the state-run Radio Lebanon, the prime minister
denied that France has put forward a suggestion on a partial
Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"I've the confidence that France would not take any step in
this direction without consultation with the Lebanese government,
and this was agreed on by us and French President Jacques Chirac,"
Hariri said, claiming that the new French government will honor
the commitments.
</P>
<P>
"There are Israeli words (on a partial withdrawal) we have heard
from time to time," he added. "If Israel really wants to withdraw
from south Lebanon, what it should do is only to implement
resolution 425."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai has reportedly
proposed that France will lead a peacekeeping force in south
Lebanon to gradually replace Israeli troops which have occupied a
border strip of the "security zone" in south Lebanon since 1985.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Maariv daily said Monday that Mordechai proposed
the suggestion at a meeting with French Defense Minister Alain
Richard in the French capital Paris last week.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted the Israeli defense minister as saying
that Israel would eventually be able to withdraw to the
international border, if the French-led multi-national force
proved able to curb the activities of the Lebanese guerrilla of
Hezbollah, or Party of God.
</P>
<P>
A today's front-page report of the Lebanese daily As-Safir
quoted French official sources as saying that France had
rejected the Israeli proposal.
</P>
<P>
"This can only be accomplished by agreement of all the parties
concerned and through a comprehensive settlement involving
Lebanon, Syria and Israel," the sources stressed.
</P>
<P>
The special report from Paris said French officials believe
the Israeli proposal was intended to pacify Israeli public
opinion which is increasingly demanding an Israeli troop
withdrawal from south Lebanon in view of the increasing Israeli
casualties caused by Hezbollah guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese militant group of Hezbollah often launches
cross-border attacks to fight against the Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Eleven Israeli soldiers have been killed and some 50 others
wounded in clashes with Hezbollah fighters on the last active
battlefront of the Arab-Israeli conflict since this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
