<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Four-Party Talks Aim to End Korean "War" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK), South Korea and the United States have agreed to
hold four-party peace talks to formally end the 1950-53 Korean
War, United States officials said today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached, Monday, after a one-day meeting of
senior officials from the three nations in a New York hotel.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement said China would join the talks, proposed by
U.S. President Bill Clinton during his visit to South Korea in
April 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The three delegations agreed that the four parties involved
will meet for preparatory talks on August 5 in New York," said a
separate statement issued by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright today.
</P>
<P>
"At that meeting, the four parties will decide the date, venue,
agenda and procedures for the formal start of four-party peace
talks," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The 1953 armistice ended the fighting in the Korea War, but
technically not the war on the Korean peninsula. The proposed
four-party peace talks are designed to replace the armistice with
a formal peace treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
