<HEADLINE> Bailey faces Challenge in Lausanne GP Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Olympic 100 meters champion Donovan
Bailey faces the fastest sprinters at the Lausanne athletics
meeting on Wednesday after he beat Michael Johnson and Linford
Christie in two 150 meters showdowns last month.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian will find out if he can defend his title at next
month's world championships in Athens when he runs 100 meters at
the Lausanne grand prix meeting.
</P>
<P>
His opponents are expected to include Namibia's Frankie
Fredericks, the Olympic silver medallist who ran 9.92 seconds last
week, bronze medallist Ato Boldon of Trinidad, whose best mark
this season was 9.89 seconds, and Britain's former world and
Olympic champion Linford Christie.
</P>
<P>
The track is fast at the Athletissima meeting. American Leroy
Burrell, who is also in the field, ran the former world record of
9.85 in the stadium in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Last season Fredericks went within 0.01 of a second of that
mark when he beat Bailey and Christie in a similar high-class
clash in Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
Bailey has been cashing in on his Atlanta success in the first
stage of the season, taking on American 200 and 400 Olympic
champion Johnson in a $1.5 million showdown over the rarely-run
150 metres in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday he made another $82,500 in just over 15 seconds when
he beat Christie in a winner-takes-all 150 metres duel in
Sheffield. 
</P>
</TEXT>
