<HEADLINE> Drums, Cymbals Mark Hong Kong Handover in Melbourne </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The beating of drums and cymbals
reached a crescendo as Chinese dragons moved through Melbourne,
marking China's resumption of the exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong in celebrations tonight.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of Chinese-Australians from more than 100 community
groups joined the dragons as they danced their way through
Chinatown to the Melbourne Town Hall.
</P>
<P>
There they took part in an international performance for more
than 2,000 guests. Melbourne is home to 160,000 Chinese.
</P>
<P>
In a blast of firecrackers, the dragons performed for several
dignitaries including Lord Mayor Ivan Deveson, state opposition
leader John Brumby and Chinese Consul-General Liang Jianming
before a cocktail party ahead of the performance, the Australian
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
The town hall celebrations followed a high-flyers' party held
by the Chinese Chamber of Commerce last evening at the Crown
Casino.
</P>
<P>
This evening's performance included Chinese dancers and singers
from Shanghai and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Organizer for the Hong Kong Return to China committee Adrienne
Farrelly said the Chinese communities in Melbourne were "over the
moon" about the handover.
</P>
<P>
She said most Chinese-Australians believed Hong Kong could only
benefit from the change.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong-born Kam Lam, who is also the president of the
Chinese Unity Association, said Hong Kong's return to China was
"fantastic".
</P>
<P>
"We have been waiting for too long," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Regardless of what political side you are on, Hong Kong
belongs to China. It's the young child returning to the mother,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
