<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Reserves up in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is sitting on foreign
exchange reserves well in excess of one billion U.S. Dollars
partly due to the coffee boom over recent years, the East Africa
Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The country has come a long way from 15 years ago when it was
down to barely three weeks' equivalent of imports in foreign
exchange reserves, said the report.
</P>
<P>
However, sceptics argue that a substantial portion of Kenya's
foreign reserves comprises so-called hot money that has come in
to take advantage of the high interests rates on the local
market, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report also warned that capital money is finding their way
out of the eastern African country because of lack of security
for investments or limited investment channels although the
Exchange Control Act is in place.
</P>
<P>
The exchange control as means to control capital is never a
solution, the report concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
