<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of
today's major Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
The major Beijing-based newspapers, including "People's Daily",
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph" and "China Daily", which were color-printed
with red-fringed titles, devoted most of their pages for the
stories on the return of Hong Kong to the motherland today.
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The paper devoted nine pages to stories on the return of
Hong Kong to the motherland on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong handover ceremony was held at the new annex of
the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center on the early
morning of July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, Premier Li Peng, Britain's
Prince Charles, Prime Minister Tony Blair and other members from
both the Chinese and British delegations attended the historic
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the event, President Jiang said that the return of
Hong Kong to the motherland shows that the development of Hong
Kong had entered a new period from that moment on.
</P>
<P>
"After the return of Hong Kong, the Chinese government will
implement the basic principles of `one country, two systems',
`Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong', and a high degree of
autonomy, maintain the original social, economic and living styles
of Hong Kong, and keep the laws of Hong Kong basically unchanged,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
-- The ceremony for the inauguration of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) and the swearing-in of the HKSAR
government was held at in the Extension to the Hong Kong
Convention and Exhibition Center (HKCEC) early this morning.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the HKSAR, and other HKSAR
government officials swore in at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The paper frontpaged President Jiang Zemin's speech at the
Hong Kong handover ceremony.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin said that "July 1, 1997 will go down in
the annals of history as a day that merits eternal memory. The
return of Hong Kong to the motherland after going through more
than one century of vicissitudes indicates that from now on, Hong
Kong compatriots have become true masters of this Chinese land
and that Hong Kong has now entered a new era of development."
</P>
<P>
The also frontpaged the speech of Premier Li Peng at the
ceremony for the inauguration of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) and the swearing-in of the HKSAR
government.
</P>
<P>
-- People from all walks of life gathered in the Extension to
the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center (HKCEC) yesterday
to celebrate the founding of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin, who is also general secretary of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) and chairman of the Central
Military Commission, delivered an important speech at the
celebration.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, who was sworn in early today as chief executive
of the HKSAR, also spoke.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The paper devoted three pages for the stories on the return
of Hong Kong to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
At an emotional and momentous ceremony in the early morning
hours today, President Jiang Zemin inaugurated the first
government of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
Administered by Premier Li Peng and witnessed by the central
government delegation, Tung Chee-Hwa was sworn in as the HKSAR's
first chief executive.
</P>
<P>
-- The carnival mood in Beijing's Tian'anmen Square reached its
peak yesterday when the countdown clock finished its historical
mission amid deafening yells and applause.
</P>
<P>
One hundred thousand revelers joined the seven-hour gala which
lasted until 5 o"clock this morning to celebrate China's
resumption of its exercise over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
-- Britain's Prince Charles and former Hong Kong governor Chris
Patten left on board the British royal yacht Britannia last night.
</P>
<P>
Prince Charles formally handed Hong Kong back to Chinese
President Jiang Zemin at midnight yesterday, marking the end of
more than 150 years of British rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
