<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Firmer as market Focus on Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
stronger against the U.S. currency here today as the market
focused on the possibilities of near-term official interest rate
movements in the United States and Australia.
</P>
<P>
The local currency closed in Sydney at 75.21 US cents from
Monday's close of 74.58 US cents, but during last night's trading
it hit a high of 75.70, its highest level since June 12.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank's manager of foreign exchange trading
Mike Eastaway said the after the Australian dollar opened around
75.48 US cents this morning, sellers had pushed the local currency
lower throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
He expected liquidity to be low in trading tonight as dealers
waited for the outcome of the two-day meeting of the U.S. Federal
Reserve's policy making arm, the Federal Open Market Committee,
which begins tonight.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Australia met today to consider monetary
policy. It last cut its official rate to 5.5 percent on May 23.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed higher against the German mark at
1.3141 marks, up from 1.2972 marks, and at 86.70 Japanese yen, up
from 85.27 yen locally Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
