<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western Germany Leads World in Labor Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The western half of Germany was the
world's most expensive labor market in 1996, a survey showed today.
</P>
<P>
The survey conducted by the Cologne-based German Economic
Institute put western German labor costs at 47.28 marks (27.07
U.S. dollars) an hour in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Even eastern Germany had labor costs of 31.89 marks (18.23
dollars) an hour, higher than all the other Group of Seven
industrialized countries except Japan which placed 11th in the
rankings with labor costs of 32.57 marks (18.62 dollars) an hour.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which chalked up the world's most expensive
labor costs in mid-1980s, placed 15th at just 26.60 marks (15.20
dollars) an hour.
</P>
<P>
The top ten in the rankings came without exception from the
European continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
