<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents of Tianjin Celebrate HK's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- More than nine million people in
Tianjin, the biggest port city of north China, are taking part in
various activities to celebrate Hong Kong's return to the
motherland after more than 156 years' colonial rule under the
British.
</P>
<P>
China resumed its exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong today.
</P>
<P>
All streets and lanes in Tianjin have been decorated with red
lanterns and colorful flags, but the most popular decoration and
symbol of national pride is the five-star national flag.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin has opened the gates of all its park free to the
public. Many of them will hold outdoor performances to mark the
arrival of the long-awaited day.
</P>
<P>
"Water Park", the city's largest, has been spruced up for the
event. A floral map of China, made from red buds and featuring
Chinese characters "Welcome Hong Kong's Return", is one of the
park's highlights.
</P>
<P>
Eight islets in the park have been planted with 1,997 colorful
flags, while scrolls bearing messages of welcome flutter high in
the sky above roads and bridges outside.
</P>
<P>
Not everyone was out playing. Workers with Dongya Woollen Mill
of Tianjin decided to spend the July 1 national holiday in their
factory to show their happiness.
</P>
<P>
Deng Weisheng, director of the mill and also a national labor
model, said that "Modern history proves that without the Communist
Party of China (CPC), there would be none of the present day's
strength and prosperity. Likewise, Dongya would not be so well
developed without reform and opening."
</P>
<P>
A major ceremony was also held by Tianjin Municipal Government
this morning in the city's stadium. About 3,000 people from the
city's professional and amateur troupes gave performances at
gathering, presided over by city mayor Zhang Lichang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
