<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Make Erratic Start to New Fiscal Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market made
an erratic start to the new financial year, sinking sharply from
the opening bell before rebounding to end only slightly weaker.
</P>
<P>
The local bourse took its initial lead from Wall Street, which
fell 14.93 points to 7,672.79 ahead of a key Federal Reserve
meeting on interest rate policy starting tonight.
</P>
<P>
Shaw Stockbrokings' Jamie Spiteri said there was also evidence
of profit-taking after the market ended the 1996-97 financial year
Monday at a new record of 2,725.9.
</P>
<P>
But a gradual recovery from mid-morning demonstrated the
ongoing support underpinning the market.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended 4.7 points lower at 2,721.2,
having traded as low as 2,701.1 and as high as 2,726.4.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index ended half a higher at 1,509.3 and the
all industrials dropped 10.8 points to 4,291.0, with interest
rate-sensitive banking stocks mostly weaker.
</P>
<P>
Intersuisse's Andrew Sekely said there may be a growing belief
that an interest rate cut was perhaps not just around the corner,
the Reserve Bank of Australia met today.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank rose 4.9 cents to 19.02 Australian
dollars but the Commonwealth Bank slipped 16 to 15.84 Australian
dollars, Westpac lost six to 7.91 Australian dollars and ANZ was
four weaker at 9.86 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Blue-chip miner BHP added 3.7 cents to 19.52 Australian
dollars, Rio Tinto lost 11 to 22.47 Australian dollars and WMC
added one to 8.36 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 366.2 million shares valued at 939.9
million Australian dollars (704.9 million US dollars) with rising
issues beating falling issues by 539 to 537.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
