<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Greets First Group of HK Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen people stayed up through
the night and gave a rapturous welcome at dawn to the first group
of Hong Kong compatriots to come back "home" over the Lo Wu Bridge
in south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Forty-year-old Mr. Kwan was the first Hong Kong resident to
cross into Shenzhen and be confronted by crowds singing and
dancing to celebrate a special homecoming.
</P>
<P>
"I feel so lucky to be the first to `come back home'," he said,
"I was celebrating the return all night long, so just came here
straight afterwards."
</P>
<P>
One humorous old man hurrying across the bridge at the crack of
dawn was asked why he came here so early. "I've been waiting all
my life," he replied.
</P>
<P>
Another early bird was Mr. Lo, who told reporters that he came
early for a celebratory morning tea appointment with his friends
in Shenzhen. Morning tea is a traditional breakfast event in south
China.
</P>
<P>
Lion dancers and other artists were still going strong at Lo Wu
Bridge, despite having sung and danced all through the night.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Jifeng, a farmer from Baode County in north China's Shanxi
Province carried posters bearing auspicious pictures of the
momentous event to Shenzhen so he could give them out to Hong Kong
people crossing the bridge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
