<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3rd Party Recommended for Manila Peace talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) said today that it was considering a third party to
broker the resumption of its peace negotiations with the
Philippine government.
</P>
<P>
Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for political affairs, said
in a statement that he wanted a third party to mediate in the
talks.
</P>
<P>
The MILF earlier called off the sixth round low-level meeting
between the two parties, which was scheduled for June 28-29 in the
southern North Cotabato province, following the outbreak of
hostilities there.
</P>
<P>
Government troops attacked MILF rebels last week who held
hostage some 100 persons in North Cotabato, leaving about 100
fatalities.
</P>
<P>
The fierce conflict also caused the evacuation of some 66,000
civilians. At present, the displaced are still housed at some 39
evacuation centers in North Cotabato and Maguindanao provinces.
</P>
<P>
With the prevailing situation, peace advocates had called on
the immediate resumption of talks between the two groups for the
evacuees to be able to return home.
</P>
<P>
Several related organizations and church groups proposed a
third party in a bid to bring the government and the MILF peace
panels back to the negotiating table.  
</P>
