<HEADLINE> San Francisco Mayor Anticipates Stronger Ties With Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's return to China
will present new opportunities for trade and economic cooperation
between San Francisco and Hong Kong, San Francisco Mayor said here
today.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think there will be alternations in Hong Kong," Willie
Brown said in an interview with Xinhua. "Hong Kong will remain its
position of an international financial and trade center."
</P>
<P>
With Chinese consisting of 25 percent of the population in San
Francisco, the city has strong ties with Hong Kong and other
cities of China. The mayor noted that trade and family ties
between San Francisco and Hong Kong were very strong.
</P>
<P>
Brown, who has visited Hong Kong for four times, said that he
has strong confidence in Hong Kong's future. He said he was
considering opening a trade office in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In another interview, Leland Y. Yee, Supervisor of San
Francisco, also said that the relationship between San Francisco
and Hong Kong will continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
"The Board of Supervisors have passed a resolution to continue
support of Hong Kong," Yee, an American Chinese, said. "The people
of San Francisco have always understood that Hong Kong would
eventually come back to China, so now the support of China by
Chinese community will be even greater."
</P>
<P>
Yee said as an American Chinese, he woke up early this morning
to watch TV broadcasting on Hong Kong's handover ceremony. He
said, "All Chinese Americans are very proud of the handover of
Hong Kong to China."
</P>
<P>
He said he believes China is going to get stronger and more
prosperous. 
</P>
</TEXT>
