<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Sails out of Hong Kong in Imperial Twilight (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 -- The lowering of the Union flag at midnight
June 30 marked the end of Britain's 156-year colonial rule in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
The final act of British withdrawal from Hong Kong was
performed by the royal yacht Britannia. Carrying the Prince of
Wales and the last British governor in Hong Kong, Christopher
Patten, the ship sailed out of the Victoria Harbor in the wee
hours of today.
</P>
<P>
British withdrawal began in the afternoon of July 30 at the
Government House on a hill slope in the district of Central on
Hong Kong Island, the official residence for 25 British Hong Kong
governors.
Amid a steady drizzle, Chris Patten bid farewell to this House
where he had lived for five years.
</P>
<P>
At 4:30 p.m. local time, the Governor's standard, a British
Union flag with the Hong Kong crest in the center, was lowered to
the strain of the Last Post, a traditional military farewell tune.
A stern-faced Patten, standing on a podium in front of the House,
gazed silently at the falling flag as rain seeped into his
dark-blue suit.
</P>
<P>
The lowering of the Governor standard had been standard
practice for every departing governor. But this time, there would
not be another Governor's standard raised here.
And, with the departure of the last Governor, this white mansion,
built in 1855 and renovated and expanded in the following years,
will become a place of historical interest, a museum possibly.
</P>
<P>
At 4:40, Patten, who had ruled Hong Kong for the past five
years on behalf of the British Queen, left the Government House in
a black Rolls Royce decorated with the royal emblem.
</P>
<P>
At 6:15 p.m., a formal farewell ceremony for the British side
was held at the harbor-side East Tamar site beside the Prince of
Wales Barracks, headquarters of the British armed forces in Hong
Kong. The Britannia was moored close by, ready to carry the Prince
of Wales and Chris Patten back to Britain. On a skyscraper in the
opposite direction hung a giant design of the bauhinia, a symbol
of the soon-to-be established Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region of the People's Republic of China. This formed a setting
for what is called the "sunset ceremony," the sunset of the
British empire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Sails out of Hong Kong in Imperial Twilight (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The heir to the British throne said,"...the Union Flag will be
lowered and the flag of China will fly over Hong Kong. More than
a century and a half of British administration will come to an
end."
</P>
<P>
At 7:45 pm, the Union Jack was lowered at the site of the
ceremony. One hundred and fifty-six years ago, a British naval
captain named Edward Belcher led his men in planting the first
Union Jack on Hong Kong Island, grabbing it from China. Today,
another naval soldier brought down the flag beside the Prince of
Wales Barracks on the same island.
</P>
<P>
The moment that fixed the attention of the entire world came at
midnight.
</P>
<P>
At the last minute of June 30, 1997, the British Union flag was
lowered in Hong Kong for the last time, signaling the end of 156
years of British rule here.
</P>
<P>
At zero hour, July 1, the Chinese national flag was raised
slowly on a flagpole at the venue of the Hong Kong handover
ceremony to the strain of China's national anthem, signifying the
return of Hong Kong to China.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Chinese national flag was also raised in
front of the Prince of Wales Barracks, which had been turned over
to the People's Liberation Army shortly before.
</P>
<P>
At 0:40 a.m. July 1, Prince Charles and Chris Patten, who had
just attended the handover ceremony, boarded the Britannia.
Escorted by the British navy frigate HMS Chatham and motorboats of
the Hong Kong police, the Britannia steamed away from the Victoria
Harbor and soon vanished into the night of the South China Sea.
</P>
<P>
One hundred and fifty-six years, five months and four days
elapsed between January 26, 1841, the day a British expedition
force first planted the Union Jack on Hong Kong island, and July
1, 1997, when the Chinese national flag started flying over Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Britain, or Britannia in Latin, came from the sea and departed
on the same route.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
