<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army to Leave Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Soldiers of the government army --
Uganda People's Defense Force -- will leave Kampala from August
1, 1997 and move to Bombo barracks, 32 km north of the capital,
reported ''The New Vision'' daily today.
</P>
<P>
Army sources here said that ministry of defense headquarters,
Mbuya army headquarters, Kireka barracks and family members of
soldiers here will be moved to the new premise, which until
recently was a military academy.
</P>
<P>
They said, defense headquarters will be taken over by
parliament while Kireka barracks will be taken by the Ministry of
Lands. Part of Mbuya army headquarters is to be turned into a
military hospital.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the decision was passed at the army
high command meeting at Rwakitura in southwestern Uganda, about
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
This, they said, is intended to reduce army expenditure as
well as save money for the welfare of the force.
</P>
<P>
''It was agreed upon that the army should not stay in the
middle of Kampala. It should be at least 20 miles away and that's
why Bombo was chosen,'' a source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
