<HEADLINE> Johannesburg to Set Up Municipal Police Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Johannesburg, a commercial
center in South Africa, will have its own municipal police force
before the end of this year, local daily "The Star" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Hillow Maeko, an executive of the Metropolitan Public Safety
and Emergency Services, said the force could become a reality as
early as October.
</P>
<P>
"We have done our homework on what is really needed for this
venture. We have been using traffic personnel and other security
components in our pilot projects toward the establishment of a
city police force," he said.
</P>
<P>
The size of the force, to police 5.5 million people, would be
determined by guidelines from provincial and national levels,
Maeko said.
</P>
<P>
A training academy has been identified where the officers
could be trained in accordance with standards set by the police,
the constitution and the government at national and provincial
levels.
</P>
<P>
He said it was envisaged that the force would be funded by the
Johannesburg Metropolitan Council and the private sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
