<HEADLINE> Zambia Set Higher Target for Non-traditional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has set a higher target of
400 million U.S. Dollars for its annual non-traditional exports
(NTEs) by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
In its exporter audit available here today, the Export Board
of Zambia (EBZ) said that the target is feasible because a number
of donors support improvement of the NTEs and the government is
also taking steps to improve the sector.
</P>
<P>
A summary of export findings indicates that the long term
target was set in 1990 to reach 200 million Dollar mark by the
year 2000, but this has since been met, thus there is need to
revise the figure upwards during 1995 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
The exporter audit said with declining copper earnings and
highest growth coming from NTEs, this sector remains the only
hope for Zambia to broaden its foreign exchange earnings and
diversify its exports.
</P>
<P>
The exporter audit called on the government to speed up
establishment of export zones and reintroduce special incentive
for the exporters to improve duty and tax exemption for the NTEs.
</P>
<P>
The NTEs earned Zambia 310 million Dollars in 1996, an
increase of 94 million Dollars over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
To promote the NTEs is part of the government efforts to
diversify the economy of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
