<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 07:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Air Company Expects Loss Of 35 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- EL AL, Israel's national air
carrier, is likely to end the year 1997 with a loss of 35 million
U.S. dollars largely due to the unfavorable political and security
situation, according to a report of The Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
EL AL spokesman Nachman Kleiman was quoted by the newspaper as
saying Monday that it will be a 22 percent improvement from
earlier forecasts of 45 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the state-owned company registered a loss of 83
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Kleiman said that the revised figures came as a result of the
increased revenues and profits during the current summer season.
</P>
<P>
Most of the passengers are Israelis going abroad, who are
flying in record numbers this summer, he said, adding that,
however, there are fewer tourists than those expected arriving
here.
</P>
<P>
The company attributes its losses to non-flights on Shabbat
(Jews' weekly day-off Saturday), security and the political
situation in the region, which led to widespread cancellations
last year and a failure to rekindle the interest of tourists
abroad this year.
</P>
<P>
The favorite destination for Israelis so far this summer has
been New York, although flights to Orlando of the U.S. have also
been doing very well, he said.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the U.S. Department of Transport threatened to
withdraw permission for EL AL to fly to Orlando after the
Israeli Civil Aviation Administration denied two U.S. air lines,
Tower Air and American Airlines, the right to fly between New
York and Tel Aviv via Athens. The two governments have recently
resolved the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kleiman said that there is strong government pressure on EL
AL to cut its losses ahead of the company's planned
privatization next year.
</P>
<P>
In addition to concern over who will be prepared to purchase
shares in the company if it doesn't fly on Shabbat, there is also
worry that receipts from the sale will be particularly low while
it reports annual losses.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the company is optimistic about the
future and is negotiating with Boeing to take up its option for a
fourth 747-400. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Reaffirms Support for SADC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has reaffirmed its
commitment to the Southern Africa Development Community (SADC)
and pledged to continue working for strengthening it so that it
becomes a sustainable regio development nal body.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a state banquet in honor of President Ketumile
Masire of Botswana last night, Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa
said Tanzania wants to see SADC growing into a viable, vibrant
and sustainable regional community.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa underscored that economic cooperation and integration
among African countries is not only a strategy against
marginalization, but also one of the most effective means of
strengthening and safeguarding independence, containing potential
conflicts in the continent and promoting good governance and
political decency.
</P>
<P>
"Our two countries will continue to cooperate in strengthening
SADC and make it a solid building bloc for the African Economic
Community," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said Botswana and Tanzania, having won and consolidated
their political independence, now have to address themselves to
the immense challenges of social and economic development.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian president said he was sure that President
Masire's visit to Tanzania will help to consolidate further the
traditional friendship and relations between the two nations and
open up new avenues of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also commended the visiting president for the good
management of the economy in Botswana, and said President
Masire's visit provided Tanzania with an opportunity to learn
from Botswana's experience.
</P>
<P>
President Masire arrived here for a five-day state visit to
Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
