<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New State of Emergency Bill Tabled in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A new State of Emergency
Bill, to allow for the declaration of a state of emergency that
conforms to South Africa's new constitution, has been introduced
in Parliament, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The existing State of Emergency Act was approved by the new
Parliament in 1995, but was enacted under the new constitution,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
The new constitution provides that a state of emergency may
only exist for 21 days, unless the National Assembly extends it,
and then only for a maximum of three months at a time.
</P>
<P>
Any additional extension beyond a first three-month period
will require approval by a 60 percent majority of members of the
National Assembly, following a public debate on the declaration.
</P>
<P>
Introducing the new State of Emergency Bill in Parliament,
Justice Minister Dullah Omar said: "Since it is necessary that
our emergency legislation should be in accordance with the
provisions of the new constitution, the Bill provides for the
repeal of that Act."
</P>
<P>
Omar said, however, the state of emergency could only be
declared if "the life of the nation is threatened by war, any
invasion, general insurrection, disorder, any national disaster
or any other public emergency, and the declaration is necessary
to restore peace and order".
</P>
<P>
A state of emergency may be declared in any area of the
country or in the whole country, according to the clauses of the
new legislation.
</P>
<P>
The state president is therefore empowered to make regulations
which are "necessary to restore the peace and order and to make
adequate provision for terminating the state of emergency".
</P>
<P>
The president is required to table any declaration in the
National Assembly "as soon as possible" after the declaration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
