<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Divided over New Members Prior to Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- With just a week to go before a
NATO summit to announce the first wave of new members, NATO
Secretary General Javier Solana said Monday that he had not yet
found consensus among the 16 member states on which countries to
put on the enlargement list.
</P>
<P>
But he told Belgian Television that progress had been made on
the issue, saying "we are now approaching a solution." NATO is due
to invite several applicant countries from eastern Europe to start
accession negotiations at the summit on July 8.
</P>
<P>
NATO countries have agreed to invite Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic to join the military alliance, but a row remains
over whether to invite Romania and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
Despite outspoken opposition from the United States, nine other
countries - France, Luxembourg, Belgium, Greece, Spain, Canada,
Italy, Turkey and Portugal - are pushing for the admission of
Romania and Slovenia in the first wave of new members.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. stance is supported by Germany, Britain, The
Netherlands, Iceland, Norway and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Solana said, "Some (member) countries do think that these two
(Romania and Slovenia) are important countries that can contribute
to security on the continent, therefore they will be part of NATO,
but I can't tell you when (it will happen)."
</P>
<P>
NATO sources said that the search for consensus among the
member states on enlargement proposals was likely to continue
"right up until the Madrid summit" on July 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Naval Unit Comes to HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- When petty officer second class
Hu Fangjun knotted the cable to a dock on the Stonecutters Island
this morning, the 23-year-old ended a 156-year absence of the
Chinese navy in Hong Kong, part of China's territory.
</P>
<P>
At 7:25 a.m., missile boat Shunde, the flagship of the Naval
Unit of the People's Liberation Army (PLA) Garrison in Hong Kong,
led the other nine naval vessels and arrived at the Stonecutters
Naval Base west of Kowloon in a torrential rain.
</P>
<P>
"I feel so honored and proud that I have berthed the first
Chinese naval vessel in Hong Kong within more than 150 years,"
said Hu.
</P>
<P>
In 1841, a British expeditionary force embarked on the
Possession Street on the Hong Kong Island, opposite the
Stonecutters Island, starting 156 years of Britain's colonial rule
over Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Volunteer Li Guoliang, helmsman of Shunde, was also excited.
"Every step from our departure and crossing the border to getting
berthed marks a part of history," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ships started off at 4:15 this morning from the Mawan
Harbor at the southern end of Shenzhen. At six o'clock sharp, they
crossed the border and entered Hong Kong's waters. Escorted by the
Hong Kong marine police boats, all of the ten ships were berthed
at 8:25 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Commander of the Naval Unit Zhu Yifei said the unit is the best
equipped in the Chinese navy.
</P>
<P>
"As part of the Hong Kong Garrison of the PLA," he said, "we
shall resolutely safeguard China's territorial sovereignty, and
discipline our unit in strict accordance with the Basic Law and
the Garrison Law."
</P>
<P>
At nine o'clock sharp, the naval unit got ready to carry out
its defense duty.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
