<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's 3rd Largest Party Formally Splits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's third largest party,
Jatiya (national) Party (JP), has formally split as both arch
rival sides expelled each other and claimed they are real JP.
</P>
<P>
Kazi Zafar Ahmed and Shah Moazzam Hossain, the two rebel
leaders who were earlier expelled from the JP by party chief HM
Ershad, held a one-day council session Monday and expelled HM
Ershad and two other senior leaders, Mizanur Rahman Chowdhury and
Naziur Rahman Manju.
</P>
<P>
The council session, participated by several thousand
councilors and delegates, also elected Kazi Zafar and Shah Moazzam
as co-chairmen of the breakaway faction.
</P>
<P>
However, None of the 30 JP's lawmakers and 31 JP presidium
members were seen in the council session.
</P>
<P>
Denying the lawful authority of the rebel's council session, JP
General Secretary Anwar Hussain Manju said that "the rebels have
already been expelled from the party and whichever faction Ershad
belonged to would be the real JP."
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said that the JP's split is the outcome of
political differences.
</P>
<P>
The JP led by former president Ershad, after last year's
parliamentary elections, supported Awami (people's) League to form
the government. General Secretary Anwar Hossain even joined Sheikh
Hasina's government as communication minister.
</P>
<P>
Kazi Zafar, one of the founders of JP and former prime minister
of Ershad's regime, opposed Ershad's soft attitude towards the
ruling party and asked Anwar Hossain to quit the government.
</P>
<P>
"Our party is essentially a force of patriotic and nationalist
elements with Islamic ideals," Kazi Zafar told the council
session.
</P>
<P>
While criticizing the government for its policies on issues
like transit to India, Ganges water sharing treaty, sub-regional
grouping, he urged for unity among like-minded parties for a
movement to protect the independence and sovereignty of
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Kazi Zafar, however, said that they have no intent to join the
main opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party or any other party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
