<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Judge Sacked for Granting Bail to Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A Thai senior judge who in February
freed on bail Li Yun Chung, a suspected heroin trafficker wanted
in the U.S., has been dismissed.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Judicial Commission has found evidence indicating that
the judge, Somchai Udomwong, had committed irregularities in the
release of Li Yun Chung, who jumped bail and fled to Myanmar,
where he was later re-arrested, returned to Thailand and
extradited to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Somchai is expected to face criminal charges in connection with
the Li case.
</P>
<P>
A source in the Judicial Commission said on Monday that the
panel based its guilty verdict on two key pieces of evidence -- a
land deal between Somchai and Li's broker, and records of his
telephone conversations with people known to have close relations
with Li.
</P>
<P>
Li has been charged by a U.S. court with trafficking more than
400 kilograms of heroin into the U.S. in 1991.
</P>
<P>
A Justice Ministry panel reported that Li had asked his wife,
Mayuree, to give 20 million baht (800,000 U.S. dollars) to his
lawyer to arrange for the bail.
</P>
<P>
Mayuree was also found to have paid 10 million baht (400,000
dollars) to the broker, Narat Charoensuk, who later transferred
800,000 baht (3,200 dollars) to the account of the wife of the
judge.  
</P>
</TEXT>
