<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Hopeful Of Increased Garment Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka is hopeful of an increase
in quotas for garments from the European Union (EU), according to
Ministry of Industrial Development sources today.
</P>
<P>
This follows discussions between Minister of Industrial
Development C.V. Gunaratne and European Union Ambassador Ilka
Usitalo recently here.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Sri Lanka has sought an increased quota of a
million for ladies and girls blouses for Sri Lanka from the EU.
This would absorb the production of existing and proposed new
garment factories.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted the minister as saying that the garments
which are high value added will satisfy the sophisticated demand
of customers in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's quota for 1997 for ladies and girls garments was
only 14.5 million pieces and 38 percent of this has already been
exported to countries of the EU.
</P>
<P>
In addition to a large number of garment factories set up in
Colombo areas, the government has approved 45 new factories.
Increased quotas were therefore essential to keep these production
lines in full stream, the sources noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
