<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exerpts of Tung Chee Hwa's Speech at Celebration Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, the first Chief
Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR),
delivered here today a speech titled "A Future of Excellence and
Prosperity for All" at a grand celebration party marking the
founding of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that Hong Kong has opened a new chapter in its
history in peace and solemnity, and can now move forward, on the
basis of the solid foundation of past successes and under the
guidance of the Basic Law, to a new height.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders have repeatedly reiterated that the prosperity
and stability of Hong Kong will contribute to the modernization of
the country, and that the successful implementation of "One
Country, Two Systems", "a high degree of autonomy" and "Hong Kong
people administering Hong Kong" is the first step towards the
ultimate re-unification of China, Tung noted.
</P>
<P>
He talked about challenges confronting Hong Kong, especially
about issues of great concern to people including the economy,
education, housing and care for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
"Our foremost task is to enhance Hong Kong's economic vitality
and sustain economic growth," he said, adding that the HKSAR
government will draw up a comprehensive plan and inject sufficient
resources to improve the quality of education.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government will also draw up a ten-year housing plan to
achieve a home ownership rate of 70 percent in a decade, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also announced a comprehensive policy of the SAR government
to take care of the various needs of senior citizens in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Describing Hong Kong's return to its motherland as a new
opportunity for Hong Kong's further development, Tung said that
the successful implementation of "one country, two systems"
requires Hong Kong people to develop a better understanding of the
motherland, cultivate a congenial relationship with China's
interior areas, embrace a distinctive set of values, safeguard the
rule of law, protect various freedoms, promote democracy and set a
long-term goal.
</P>
<P>
He said that due to the long separation, there is a general
lack of understanding about the motherland among the people of
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong "has created a new environment and
better conditions for us to understand our country and our people,
and to love our country and our people", he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the understanding and relationship between Hong
Kong and the interior areas must be strengthened through mutual
trust, mutual economic benefits, cultural interaction, and mutual
respect for each other's way of life.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that Hong Kong and the interior areas
will move forward together, hand in hand.
</P>
<P>
He said that the SAR government would continue to encourage
diversity in the Hong Kong society, but should also reaffirm and
respect the fine traditional Chinese values.
</P>
<P>
"We value plurality, but discourage open confrontation; we
strive for liberty, but not at the expense of the rule of law; we
respect minority views, but are mindful of wider interests; we
protect individual rights, but also shoulder collective
responsibilities," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the HKSAR would continue to ensure that the
executive, legislative and judicial branches of the government
operate independently, and would keep up efforts against
corruption and maintain a clean society.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR will also ensure equality before the law, he said.
</P>
<P>
He pledged that the SAR government would preserve the existing
freedoms and lifestyle of the Hong Kong people, and ensure that
Hong Kong people continue to enjoy the freedoms of speech,
assembly, association, the press and other freedoms guaranteed by
the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights.
</P>
<P>
"The SAR government will resolutely move forward to a more
democratic form of government in accordance with provisions in the
Basic Law, and provide opportunities for every stratum of the
society and legitimate political organizations, and people with
different shades of opinion, to participate in the political
process," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he would work together with the local civil service to
serve the community and help build a better Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time in the history of Hong Kong, we now have
the opportunity to chart our own destiny," he said.
</P>
<P>
He finally described an ideal Hong Kong society in his vision
as having the following characteristics:
-- a society proud of its national identity and cultural
</P>
<P>
heritage;
-- a stable, equitable, free, democratic, compassionate society
</P>
<P>
with a clear sense of direction;
-- an affluent society with improved quality of life for all;
-- a decent society with a level playing field and fair
</P>
<P>
competition under the rule of law;
-- a window for exchanges between China and the rest of the
</P>
<P>
world;
-- a renowned international financial, trading, transportation
</P>
<P>
and communication center;
-- a world class cultural, education and scientific research
</P>
<P>
center.
</P>
</TEXT>
