<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs From Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from the Southern Common Market (Mercosur), a
regional economic bloc grouping Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay,
Uruguay and Chile.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's industrial export to Mercosur countries
between October 1996 to February 1997 totaled 495.7 million
U.S. dollars, up 34 percent over the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
That export accounted for 71.7 percent of Chile's total foreign
sales, which, in the same period of the year before, accounted
only for 57.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Foreign investments in Argentina amounted to
21.503 billion dollars in May, up 74.7 percent over the same month
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Belgium lead with 7.07 billion dollars, accounting for 32.9
percent of Argentina's total foreign investment, followed by the
United States with 7.02 billion dollars, the National Securities
Commission said.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- The Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) granted
a 100 million-dollar loan to Argentina to finance a project
designed to sharpen the competitive edge of small and medium-sized
businesses.
</P>
<P>
The loan is earmarked for technical assistance and training
programs for industrial development, and for information
publication on business opportunities and successful business
practices.
</P>
<P>
The IDB finalized a 3 million-dollar loan to two enterprises
for purchasing three barges to transport liquid propane gas.
</P>
</TEXT>
