<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico-U.S. Trade Up 60 Percent in Three Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Mexico and the
United States increased by about 60 percent in the past three
years as a result of the enforcement of the North American Free
Trade Agreement (NAFTA), the local press today quoted experts as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Sidney Weintraub, an economist, believes that part of the
growth in trade was due to the continuation of pre-NAFTA
tendencies, but part was indeed due to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Weintraub, a political economist with the Center of
International and Strategic Studies, said U.S. exports to Mexico
resumed their upward trend last year after a decline in 1995.
</P>
<P>
U.S. sales to Mexico increased by about 24 percent from 46
billion U.S. dollars in 1995, a year of recession in Mexico, to
more than 57 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, U.S. exports to its southern neighbor have risen more
quickly, which enabled Mexico to become the second biggest market
for U.S. products in May.
</P>
<P>
Weintraub predicted that bilateral trade will exceed 150
billion dollars in 1997, which will make NAFTA one of the broadest
trade relations in the world.
</P>
<P>
Joseph McKinney, an economist and academic at Bayloy University
in Waco, Texas, said that the effects of the agreement on the
U.S. economy have been positive and relatively modest.
</P>
<P>
As for the controversial topic of whether jobs were created or
lost in the United States because of the NAFTA, McKinney denied
there is any correlation between general job levels and trade
deficits.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. economy generated a net increase of more than
8 million jobs since January 1, 1994, when NAFTA became
effective. The unemployment rate now is nearly 2 percentage
points lower than it was in 1993, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
