<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seles Becomes 8th Women's Seed Casualty at Wimbledon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Second seed Monica Seles of the
United States became the 8th women's seed casualty after losing an
astonishing match to unseeded French player Sandrine Testud at the
Wimbledon tennis championships here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Seles kicked off with great form by snatching the set 6-0,
giving her opponent on chance of gaining an upper hand. But
strong-willed Testud made a dramatic comeback by winning the
following two sets 6-4 8-6, throwing the major seed out of the
Championships.
</P>
<P>
"I was playing so well in the first set and at the beginning of
the second," Seles told a press briefing after the match. "I was
up 5-2 then I had the match point...I should never have let her
back into the match."
</P>
<P>
"I missed a couple of shots that she was out of contention of
getting and they were key shots a few times," Seles said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the other remaining women's seeds including Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario, third seed Jana Novotna, Mary Pearce of France
and Mary Joe Fernadez of the United States entered the fourth
round by defeating their opponents in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
In sharp contrast with the heavy casualties of women's seeds,
world number one player Pete Sampras, three times Wimbledon men's
champion Boris Becker and third seed Yevgeny Kafelnikov have
cruised into the next round after trouncing their opponents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Return of Hong Kong Success of Chinese Policies: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Speaker of Pakistan's National
Assembly Ellahi Buksh Soomro said today the resumption of the
exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong by China was the success of
the Chinese social, economic and diplomatic polices.
</P>
<P>
"We are as happy as the Chinese people over these
celebrations," Soomoro said when attending the reception hosted by
the Chinese Ambassador in Islamabad, Zhang Chengli, here at the
Chinese Embassy,
</P>
<P>
Chief of Pakistan's Army Staff General Jahangir Karamat also
said on the occasion that the return of Hong Kong to China "is a
great occasion."
</P>
<P>
"We share these happiest moments with our Chinese brothers,"
Karamat said.
</P>
<P>
Former care-taker prime minister Malik Meraj Khalid said that
the return of Hong Kong to China testify to the fact that China
was emerging as a strong power of the world. The Chinese struggle
for their rights "is a beaming example for other nations to
emulate".
</P>
<P>
Former caretaker prime minister Ghulam Mustafa Jatoi, who also
attended the reception said this was a great moment for the
nations "which believe in national sovereignty and independence."
</P>
<P>
He said, "we whole-heartedly join our Chinese friends in their
happiness and progress".
</P>
<P>
The reception was attended by about 800 guests including senior
Pakistani officials, diplomats and reporters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
