<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> National Flag Raising Ceremony on First Day of Hong Kong's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A new day was dawning in the
Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The boiling Tian'anmen Square was beginning to get quieter
following an all-night celebration as the 100,000-plus crowd
were eagerly awaiting the appearance of the Five-Star Red Flag,
China's national flag.
</P>
<P>
Out of the giant gates of Tian'anmen, Liu Yaozheng, with the
huge flag on his shoulder, led a team of 36 armed police soldiers
and a 60-member band, all in full military attire into the square.
</P>
<P>
This was the 263rd mission of the 20-year-old soldier. "It's
the most special one," he said before the troops left the barracks
in a compound inside the Forbidden City. "I will say this to
myself repeatedly when I march out."
</P>
<P>
Liu was the flag-holder on the first morning when Hong Kong
shares the national flag with the rest parts of China. "The flag
is the symbol of our nation and sovereignty, I feel so proud that
I can carry and escort it today," he said.
</P>
<P>
The rank and file marched cross the Chang'an Avenue and reached
the base of a 30-meter-high staff, which was surrounded by the
waiting crowd. Closest to the staff was a ring of 56 young men and
women, all dressed up in ethnic-style costumes, symbolizing the
unity of the 56 nationalities of the nation.
</P>
<P>
At 4:50 sharp, Beijing time, when the sun sent out its first
ray over the eastern horizon, the flag began to rise while the
band played the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
All soluted. The 100,000 people sang "March of the Volunteers,"
China's national anthem.
</P>
<P>
Four hours and fifty minutes ago, the same flag rose for the
first time ever over Hong Kong, a territory ceded to the British
rule after the Opium War in 1842.
</P>
<P>
"Now I am home," said Simon Yong who flew from Hong Kong
yesterday specially for the Beijing celebrations." He felt so
emotional that tears welled up in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
Quivering with excitement, Zhai Xiurong, 63, told Xinhua that
he watched from afar the raising of the national flag at the
inauguration ceremony of the People's Republic 48 years ago when
Chairman Mao Zedong declared that the Chinese people had stood
up. Now I saw it right under it. It has convinced me that our
nation is becoming ever stronger."
</P>
<P>
After the flag was flying in the breeze, there was a
thunderous outburst of applause among the crowd that echoed over
the square.
</P>
<P>
Hand in hand, shoulder by shoulder, thousands of college
students waved flags, tossed colorful ribbons and danced in light
steps while singing "Ode to the Motherland", which starts with the
stanza "The Five-Star Red Flag is fluttering in the wind."
</P>
<P>
"There is a sure way to make our country strong," said Lin Wei,
an electronic engineering major from Beijing University. "Tomorrow
is ours. We rejoice over Hong Kong's return, but the reunification
of the whole nation is yet to be accomplished. It is up to us
young people to shoulder the sacred historical mission and
accomplish it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
