<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial Begins on Germany's Biggest Bankruptcy Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The trial opened today in Frankfurt
of German real estate developer Juergen Schneider on several
charges of fraud and credit fraud in the multi-billion dollar
collapse of his company in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The trial came more than three years after Schneider, 63,
suddenly went missing in April 1994, leaving behind a company in
debts of about 5.4 billion marks (3.2 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Schneider and his wife Claudia were arrested in Florida, the
United States, in May, 1995 and extradited to Germany in February,
1996.
</P>
<P>
He was found to have cheated about 50 banks of loans for his
projects. The Schneiders were also charged with fraudulent
bankruptcy involving some 245 million marks which they allegedly
diverted to Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Schneider began his business in real estate in 1981. At the
prime of his career, he was involved in prime-location real estate
projects in 14 cities, building luxury hotels, office buildings
and shopping arcades. His company once owned 168 real estate
properties.
</P>
<P>
About 2.6 billion mark debts of his company remains now
uncovered despite the sale of most of these assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970701.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Rises to 3 Year High Against Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar set a nearly
40-month high against the mark Monday on continued strength of the
British pound against the German currency and suggestions that
criteria for the common European currency may have to be eased.
</P>
<P>
By the day's end in New York, the dollar had risen to 1.7443
marks from 1.7387 on Friday, its highest close since February
1994. It hit 1.7465 earlier, its loftiest intraday level since
then.
</P>
<P>
The dollar rose also to 114.59 yen, up from 114.55. The pound
advanced to 1.6647 U.S. dollars from 1.6639 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Some strong economic data out of the United States also helped
the dollar, particularly since it came on the eve of a meeting of
the Federal Reserve policy-makers who set interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Other dollar rates in New York, compared with Friday: 1.4610
Swiss francs, up from 1.4544; 5.8755 French francs, up from 5.8630;
1,695.00 Italian lire, down from 1,697.00; and 1.3803 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.3799.  
</P>
</TEXT>
